I would like to draw your attention to the fact that China is the leader in the current conditions of the world trade in terms of growth rates, but the level of income of the population of one country or another, the population, just determines which group will be related to developed or developing countries.

01:23:39.000 --> 01:24:07.000
Look at the next slide. Here are examples of developing countries, Vietnam and India. Vietnam has recently begun to develop industries related to the production of light industry in the factories of this country and is included in the world integration processes at the level of such detailed or operational division of labor.

01:24:07.000 --> 01:24:24.000
And the income of the population of Vietnam, GDP per capita, is quite low, which allows Vietnam to be considered a low-income country. This is only $ 822 per capita.

01:24:24.000 --> 01:24:36.000
If we take India, the level of income per capita is slightly higher, but also quite low. Now let's pay attention to China.

01:24:36.000 --> 01:24:59.000
I have already said that China is rapidly developing an export-oriented sector due to significant capital investments in the southern regions of the country, an industrial enclave, focused on international consumer demand.

01:25:00.000 --> 01:25:20.000
The level of income per capita is already $ 2,000, even more than $ 2,000, which shows that the group of developing countries is quite diverse, but China is still among the developing countries.

01:25:20.000 --> 01:25:42.000
Although, analyzing its rapid foreign economic activity, China says that they cannot be called catching up with the economy, because they lead in growth, in the development of the internal product, in the growth of export and import.

01:25:42.000 --> 01:26:10.000
Although, the current programs in the national macroeconomy make the pace of rapid growth slightly lower, because the rate of growth is maintained at the level of 19%, but the export is 26% in 2003, a little bit of export in 2007, 19%, and nevertheless, these are quite high indicators.

01:26:10.000 --> 01:26:26.000
Thus, China, being a serious competitor to developed countries in the international trade market, remains the leader in foreign trade, but so far it is a developing country.

01:26:26.000 --> 01:26:40.000
For comparison, the level of GDP per capita for the country to become a group of medium-developed countries should be about $ 6,000.

01:26:41.000 --> 01:26:56.000
For comparison, the level of GDP per capita for the developed countries of the United States is about $ 45,000.

01:26:56.000 --> 01:27:13.000
Of course, the United States is not the leader in this respect, but the pace of economic growth is at 2% for the growth of GDP, and at 5-6% for export and import.

01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:34.000
In general, the pace of foreign trade and the development of foreign trade in developed countries is much lower than that of developing countries.

01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:59.000
For example, the new market economy can serve Russia, and despite the fact that we are a large country in terms of territory and economy, the growth indicators of large industrial countries are usually small enough,

01:27:59.000 --> 01:28:10.000
but in comparison with the 2% that we have just seen in the United States, the growth of GDP is at 8-6%.

01:28:10.000 --> 01:28:20.000
Accordingly, both export and import have a fairly dynamic pace of development, from 6% to 15%.

01:28:21.000 --> 01:28:40.000
The tendency is that in the last three years our pure export has suddenly begun to decrease due to the fact that, as a result of the Central Bank's estimates, the ruble price is increasing,

01:28:40.000 --> 01:28:57.000
and, accordingly, our companies and economic agents in the form of households are able to buy and purchase more goods and services for the existing ruble.

01:28:57.000 --> 01:29:21.000
That is why in recent years we have seen an increase in certain imports compared to exports. Nevertheless, the balance of payments in Russia is positive, and such a tendency does not threaten the payment capacity of the country, its currency exchange rate and trade balance.

01:29:22.000 --> 01:29:27.000
What is the trade structure of foreign trade for all countries?

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:36.000
I would like to emphasize that it is for all countries, because the global demand will be dictated by developed countries.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:49.000
And if even developing countries, such as China, are trying to develop their exports, then the main consumers for China are developed countries.

01:29:49.000 --> 01:29:58.000
Based on this, the flows to developed countries, the flows of supply of goods will come from the structure of demand that is adopted in developed countries.

01:29:58.000 --> 01:30:07.000
Look, three quarters of the production is the processing industry, while the equipment and transport are occupied by half of this group.

01:30:07.000 --> 01:30:21.000
The next subgroup is chemistry, black colored metals. This subgroup is also dominant and, therefore, supplements the equipment and transport.

01:30:22.000 --> 01:30:38.000
To a lesser extent, the production of the processing industry is associated with the movement of the light industry, but textile is still one component of the global trade.

01:30:38.000 --> 01:30:45.000
And one quarter of the foreign trade flows fall on raw materials and food.

01:30:45.000 --> 01:31:06.000
Such a ratio of processing products and raw materials indicates that countries that develop their foreign trade based on raw materials or food supply have some economic growth limitations,

01:31:07.000 --> 01:31:16.000
because the demand for raw materials and food is stable and, as economists say, it is not elastic in price.

01:31:16.000 --> 01:31:24.000
That is, even if prices fall for this commodity, the demand for raw materials and food will not increase sharply.

01:31:24.000 --> 01:31:27.000
There is a certain level of consumption.

01:31:28.000 --> 01:31:34.000
But the demand for equipment, for various modifications of its appearance, can be overshadowed by the technical progress.

01:31:34.000 --> 01:31:46.000
And, accordingly, new goods or services will always be offered, which will allow consumers to pay attention to them and eventually purchase.

01:31:47.000 --> 01:31:58.000
Therefore, if a country is trying to join the modern world economy, if a country is trying to win certain positions in this world economy and not be only a raw material addict,

01:31:58.000 --> 01:32:06.000
and, accordingly, depend on world prices, then it must definitely try to increase the share of the processing industry.

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:13.000
Then it has a chance to become a more developed market economy with, say, a transition economy.

01:32:13.000 --> 01:32:23.000
The general trend of the pace of growth of world trade is that the pace of growth of foreign trade for a long enough period,

01:32:23.000 --> 01:32:29.000
probably for about 50 years, exceeds the pace of growth of industrial production.

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:36.000
This is precisely due to the fact that, as I said, the detailed and operational division of labor

01:32:37.000 --> 01:32:47.000
makes it possible to organize such flows as the flow of components, some semi-finished products, which are collected in third countries.

01:32:47.000 --> 01:32:59.000
And another trend that we talked about is the pace of growth of trade in developing countries is higher than the pace of growth of trade in developed countries.

01:32:59.000 --> 01:33:10.000
What are the reasons for export-oriented development of certain countries, and, in particular, the reasons for export-oriented development,

01:33:10.000 --> 01:33:13.000
which are chosen by developing countries?

01:33:13.000 --> 01:33:23.000
The so-called new industrial countries of the first and second wave, which, based on their macroeconomic policy,

01:33:23.000 --> 01:33:30.000
in the 1960s, set the development of export-oriented world demand for industries,

01:33:30.000 --> 01:33:43.000
their activity shows that they have won in such a competitive struggle, and their income level for the longer term population, i.e., GDP for the longer term population, is growing.

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:47.000
What are the reasons for this?

01:33:47.000 --> 01:33:50.000
First of all, initially, the internal demand is limited.

01:33:50.000 --> 01:33:59.000
Of course, if we look not at the GDP for the longer term population, but at the real income of the population,

01:33:59.000 --> 01:34:06.000
the indicator will be several times lower than the GDP.

01:34:06.000 --> 01:34:16.000
Accordingly, the internal demand is limited by the purchasing power of the population and does not have such expanded capabilities.

01:34:17.000 --> 01:34:25.000
On the other hand, as soon as countries focused on export develop and achieve certain success,

01:34:25.000 --> 01:34:32.000
and China is an example of this, then part of the industry can be reoriented to internal demand.

01:34:32.000 --> 01:34:41.000
In the strategic projects of China's development, the Chinese government lays down elements of stimulating internal demand,

01:34:41.000 --> 01:34:46.000
hoping that the growth of the income level of the population, the real income of the population,

01:34:46.000 --> 01:34:53.000
which is also related to the fact that they were engaged in export industries and received higher incomes, higher wages,

01:34:53.000 --> 01:34:58.000
will now stimulate further development of the industry.

01:34:58.000 --> 01:35:09.000
Such export-oriented economies as China, probably, with the growth of internal demand, will depend less on international demand and international cataclysms.

01:35:10.000 --> 01:35:21.000
The next factor of export-oriented development is, of course, the availability of cheap labor resources or other natural resources.

01:35:21.000 --> 01:35:30.000
By excess, I mean that the internal industry, the internal production demand does not meet the needs of these resources,

01:35:30.000 --> 01:35:33.000
and, most likely, there is a high unemployment.

01:35:33.000 --> 01:35:43.000
In this case, one of the methods of getting out of the situation when the industry, which is oriented to the internal market,

01:35:43.000 --> 01:35:55.000
does not need so many workers, is the exit of the production, which is oriented only to export and global demand.

01:35:56.000 --> 01:36:08.000
The next reason why countries that have chosen export-oriented production get an advantage is, first of all, the possibility of attracting foreign investments.

01:36:08.000 --> 01:36:21.000
All new industrial countries have just carried out their industrialization due to the fact that the capital flow from developed countries,

01:36:21.000 --> 01:36:32.000
and direct foreign investments, that is, the factories and factories that were on the territory of developed countries,

01:36:32.000 --> 01:36:41.000
were limited in their expansion precisely because in developed countries there is no fresh labor flow on the one hand,

01:36:41.000 --> 01:36:48.000
and on the other hand, the level of wages and, accordingly, the costs for companies are quite high.

01:36:49.000 --> 01:37:00.000
And so, the same example that was already given in the earlier tables, for example, China at the current stage is no longer the cheapest factory in the world,

01:37:00.000 --> 01:37:05.000
and the level of income of the population is increasing due to the increase in wages.

01:37:05.000 --> 01:37:13.000
But another, for example, a block like Vietnam, where you can organize cheaper production,

01:37:13.000 --> 01:37:21.000
and, accordingly, this attracts foreign investors, and from the point of view of a country's profit, this is the acquisition of new technologies.

01:37:21.000 --> 01:37:27.000
Moreover, technologies will be associated not only with production processes, but also with new technologies of management and marketing,

01:37:27.000 --> 01:37:37.000
which gives the opportunity to transition economies, for example, or developing countries that have recently embarked on the market path of development,

01:37:38.000 --> 01:37:46.000
to attract advanced technologies into the organization of production, which can give a kind of a multiplied effect.

01:37:46.000 --> 01:37:51.000
What are the consequences of global trade?

01:37:51.000 --> 01:37:58.000
On the one hand, it could be said that there are two negative factors,

01:37:59.000 --> 01:38:03.000
that is, the increase in dependence on exports and the increase in dependence on imports.

01:38:03.000 --> 01:38:12.000
But, in principle, probably for an economy that is developing quite stably, such dependence is not scary.

01:38:12.000 --> 01:38:21.000
And we have already said that, for example, for small European countries, the export or import quota is more than 100%.

01:38:21.000 --> 01:38:30.000
On the other hand, for large economies with a large national market, such as Russia and the United States, the export quota reaches only 20%,

01:38:30.000 --> 01:38:33.000
so the dependence here is relatively high.

01:38:33.000 --> 01:38:44.000
The next consequence of the development of global trade is the consequence of a positive nature for consumers of the national economy.

01:38:45.000 --> 01:38:55.000
Of course, imports lead to a decrease in domestic prices and an increase in the assortment to satisfy consumer demand.

01:38:55.000 --> 01:39:05.000
Another consequence of which, so to speak, national economic agents benefit from is the leveling of the income level of workers.

01:39:05.000 --> 01:39:10.000
An example of such leveling of the level of workers can be the Japanese.

01:39:10.000 --> 01:39:20.000
In post-war Japan, both national industries focused on national demand and export demand were developing rapidly.

01:39:20.000 --> 01:39:30.000
This is because a sufficiently qualified Japanese labor force had a fairly low income level, and, accordingly, a low level of costs for companies.

01:39:31.000 --> 01:39:39.000
But if we compare it to the modern period, then such an economic growth has gradually leveled the income level,

01:39:39.000 --> 01:39:44.000
and now the income level of the average wage in Japan is higher than in the United States.

01:39:44.000 --> 01:39:57.000
Therefore, in general, for developing countries, in the long term, the development of export-oriented production is a positive moment.

01:39:57.000 --> 01:40:09.000
The next consequence, as I said, is the development of export-oriented industries, and there is a contradiction here.

01:40:09.000 --> 01:40:13.000
And these contradictions are related to the position of the Dutch disease.

01:40:13.000 --> 01:40:20.000
I repeat, the Dutch disease is a disproportionate development of export industries,

01:40:20.000 --> 01:40:33.000
and within these contradictions, the creation of such a situation, when the income of the owners of the production factors in export industries is much higher than in import-replacing countries.

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:40.000
And the import-replacing countries, the industries, still suffer from the fact that they do not have enough resources,

01:40:40.000 --> 01:40:46.000
and, in the end, a certain economic decline in the economy is possible.

01:40:46.000 --> 01:40:51.000
And the last effect of the Dutch disease is the increase in the national currency exchange rate.

01:40:51.000 --> 01:40:56.000
Again, if the export is developing in large volumes and higher than the import,

01:40:56.000 --> 01:41:03.000
then the inflow of foreign currency into the country will ultimately lead to an increase in the national currency exchange rate,

01:41:03.000 --> 01:41:10.000
and this national currency will lead to relative increase in its prices for export goods.

01:41:11.000 --> 01:41:18.000
And the last consequence of global trade, which I would like to draw your attention to, is integration.

01:41:18.000 --> 01:41:30.000
Integration is, of course, a positive process, but it is connected with two trends, which we will talk about a little later.

01:41:31.000 --> 01:41:40.000
The consequences are connected with the fact that, on the one hand, the integration unions liberalize foreign trade between countries,

01:41:40.000 --> 01:41:47.000
but, on the other hand, the production of a single foreign rate can reduce trade flows with third-party countries,

01:41:47.000 --> 01:41:52.000
and this will have negative consequences for global trade.

01:41:52.000 --> 01:41:59.000
Nevertheless, the more integration unions are developed, the more countries are included in such integration unions,

01:41:59.000 --> 01:42:05.000
the greater the effect of countries involved in it.

01:42:08.000 --> 01:42:16.000
The next form of economic foreign trade is international credit relations.

01:42:17.000 --> 01:42:26.000
First of all, credit relations, let's say, in the more ancient centuries, in the 16th, 17th, 18th centuries,

01:42:26.000 --> 01:42:36.000
arose precisely because foreign trade had to be credited, and therefore the first and most important reason for the development of foreign trade

01:42:36.000 --> 01:42:41.000
is, in the end, the development of international credit relations.

01:42:42.000 --> 01:42:51.000
The growth of ship capital in the national economy, in the end, reaches such limits that it turns out to be superfluous,

01:42:51.000 --> 01:43:00.000
and does not find a profitable sphere of acceptance with the profit margin that the owners of this capital would like to receive in the national economy,

01:43:00.000 --> 01:43:03.000
and then it goes beyond the national framework.

01:43:04.000 --> 01:43:08.000
The next reason is the introduction of international accounts.

01:43:08.000 --> 01:43:11.000
I mean interstate relations.

01:43:11.000 --> 01:43:17.000
In this case, if we have a negative trade and a negative payment balance,

01:43:17.000 --> 01:43:29.000
then credit relations with countries, both private and state creditors, help countries to balance their financial system.

01:43:30.000 --> 01:43:32.000
What are the forms of lending?

01:43:32.000 --> 01:43:40.000
First of all, you can consider the forms of lending depending on the flows associated with this lending.

01:43:40.000 --> 01:43:43.000
First of all, the forms of lending of exports.

01:43:43.000 --> 01:43:48.000
This is shown in the scheme of commercial and bank loans.

01:43:48.000 --> 01:43:56.000
Commercial loans are associated with the activities of companies that trade and lend to each other in these processes,

01:43:56.000 --> 01:44:03.000
and bank loans are a separate service of the banking sphere for the purpose of trading.

01:44:03.000 --> 01:44:09.000
In this case, the forms of such lending can be consumer, sorry,

01:44:09.000 --> 01:44:14.000
purchasing contributions issued by the exporter to one or another country, a foreign manufacturer,

01:44:14.000 --> 01:44:22.000
ships for goods located within the country, loans for goods and goods documents in the country of export,

01:44:22.000 --> 01:44:28.000
and bank loans, again, for loans in the country of the exporter.

01:44:28.000 --> 01:44:32.000
Commercial or corporate loans of the importer.

01:44:32.000 --> 01:44:40.000
In this case, the forms of such a loan are open credit,

01:44:40.000 --> 01:44:46.000
when the exporter writes down the importer's debt, the value of sold and unloaded goods,

01:44:46.000 --> 01:44:49.000
and the importer must pay off the loan in the established period.

01:44:49.000 --> 01:44:51.000
Vexel loan.

01:44:51.000 --> 01:44:59.000
The exporter makes a deal on the sale of goods in a loan and issues a demand to the importer for payment.

01:44:59.000 --> 01:45:01.000
Private insurance.

01:45:01.000 --> 01:45:07.000
In this case, the insurance of foreign trade relations, insurance companies,

01:45:07.000 --> 01:45:11.000
and then the insurance company takes the risks of payment.

01:45:11.000 --> 01:45:13.000
State guarantees.

01:45:13.000 --> 01:45:19.000
This area is developing especially rapidly in the last 20 years,

01:45:19.000 --> 01:45:27.000
and all the most developed countries in the world have state support for stimulating their exports.

01:45:27.000 --> 01:45:33.000
And then the state insures not only from economic, but also political risks

01:45:33.000 --> 01:45:37.000
that can damage the foreign trade flow.

01:45:38.000 --> 01:45:43.000
What is the structure of a bank loan on import?

01:45:43.000 --> 01:45:50.000
First of all, this is a loan issued with the agreement of the importer's bank to pay the demand of the exporter.

01:45:50.000 --> 01:45:53.000
That is, a loan issued with an acceptance.

01:45:53.000 --> 01:45:56.000
The next form is an acceptance-reimbursement loan.

01:45:56.000 --> 01:46:02.000
In this case, Vexel is accepted by the bank on the condition of receiving a guarantee on it

01:46:02.000 --> 01:46:05.000
from the foreign bank of the importer.

01:46:05.000 --> 01:46:10.000
The next form is a direct bank loan to foreign buyers.

01:46:10.000 --> 01:46:15.000
It is quite interesting to develop credit lines

01:46:15.000 --> 01:46:20.000
when large banks open credit lines for foreign trade transactions

01:46:20.000 --> 01:46:25.000
to their permanent clients on export-import relations.

01:46:25.000 --> 01:46:31.000
That is, this is a situation when payments are practically immediate.

01:46:31.000 --> 01:46:32.000
Factoring.

01:46:32.000 --> 01:46:37.000
In this case, the exporter who sold the goods on the condition of a loan

01:46:37.000 --> 01:46:40.000
receives a number of services from the factoring company

01:46:40.000 --> 01:46:44.000
in the form of acquiring a position, accounting for export requirements,

01:46:44.000 --> 01:46:47.000
and making payments.

01:46:47.000 --> 01:46:48.000
Leasing.

01:46:48.000 --> 01:46:52.000
The transfer of legal property rights to consumers of goods.

01:46:52.000 --> 01:46:59.000
But since the right to property in the framework of leasing transactions continues gradually,

01:46:59.000 --> 01:47:04.000
the buyer does not have to buy equipment immediately, for example,

01:47:04.000 --> 01:47:06.000
when paying leasing payments.

01:47:06.000 --> 01:47:08.000
Thus, the payment is postponed.

01:47:08.000 --> 01:47:10.000
Compensation transactions.

01:47:10.000 --> 01:47:15.000
This form of lending is also developing quite successfully

01:47:15.000 --> 01:47:18.000
between stable partners,

01:47:18.000 --> 01:47:23.000
especially partners that are associated with contracts on customs goods.

01:47:23.000 --> 01:47:29.000
That is, it is assumed that the supplier of raw materials and components

01:47:29.000 --> 01:47:32.000
supplies the product on a loan,

01:47:32.000 --> 01:47:38.000
and the company in another country, which imports this raw material and components,

01:47:38.000 --> 01:47:46.000
in the future pays a share of the finished product for the supply of raw materials and components.

01:47:46.000 --> 01:47:52.000
Insurance of multinational contracts.

01:47:52.000 --> 01:47:58.000
Of course, such contracts that are associated with multinational corporations

01:47:58.000 --> 01:48:01.000
are insured primarily by multinational banks

01:48:01.000 --> 01:48:04.000
or national state companies,

01:48:04.000 --> 01:48:10.000
since the volume of turnover is large enough, as well as the volume of risk.

01:48:10.000 --> 01:48:14.000
Thus, the international loan, as we see,

01:48:14.000 --> 01:48:19.000
is divided into three subgroups, private, state, and private-state.

01:48:20.000 --> 01:48:24.000
If we have a country that is credited,

01:48:24.000 --> 01:48:26.000
there is an interstate loan,

01:48:26.000 --> 01:48:30.000
it is assumed that the loan is issued by one government to another.

01:48:30.000 --> 01:48:33.000
What funds are used for such lending?

01:48:33.000 --> 01:48:36.000
These are funds of the state budget,

01:48:36.000 --> 01:48:41.000
or funds of specialized state or semi-state banks,

01:48:41.000 --> 01:48:46.000
such as, for example, Vneshtorbank or Sberbank for the Russian Federation,

01:48:46.000 --> 01:48:48.000
that is, in addition to the central bank.

01:48:48.000 --> 01:48:51.000
When interstate lending is carried out,

01:48:51.000 --> 01:48:59.000
it is assumed that all countries of the world are interested in the absence of destabilization of the financial market and financial system.

01:48:59.000 --> 01:49:05.000
Therefore, it is more important for them that there are no economic cataclysms in one country or another,

01:49:05.000 --> 01:49:10.000
since this country will offer some goods for export,

01:49:10.000 --> 01:49:15.000
as well as buy imports from developed or developing countries.

01:49:16.000 --> 01:49:23.000
Accordingly, countries interested in the framework of international relations

01:49:23.000 --> 01:49:26.000
provide loans at the state level.

01:49:26.000 --> 01:49:31.000
In this regard, the table presented on the next slide is an interesting one.

01:49:31.000 --> 01:49:35.000
This is the structure of the external debt of the Russian Federation.

01:49:35.000 --> 01:49:43.000
As you can see, the debt of the former USSR is 56 billion dollars,

01:49:44.000 --> 01:49:50.000
compared to the debt of the former USSR, which was about 140 billion dollars 10 years ago.

01:49:50.000 --> 01:49:55.000
We are constantly increasing this debt in a certain structure.

01:49:55.000 --> 01:50:00.000
On the other hand, pay attention to the line of the new Russian debt.

01:50:00.000 --> 01:50:06.000
It is assumed that the loans at the level of government loans are still profitable,

01:50:07.000 --> 01:50:13.000
and not only to the central government, but especially to the regional level,

01:50:13.000 --> 01:50:18.000
for example, to the level of Moscow, the subject of the Russian Federation.

01:50:18.000 --> 01:50:28.000
Accordingly, these state bodies take loans under their own state programs.

01:50:29.000 --> 01:50:35.000
As you can see, the tendency is that on the one hand,

01:50:35.000 --> 01:50:40.000
state loans tend to decrease,

01:50:40.000 --> 01:50:47.000
and private loans, that is, loans from private banks, tend to increase.

01:50:47.000 --> 01:50:54.000
Moreover, private banks or private companies of Russia are in charge of lending on the private banks' line.

01:50:55.000 --> 01:51:01.000
The general tendency is that the structure of the external debt is transformed

01:51:01.000 --> 01:51:09.000
from the state government external debt to the private external debt of the Russian Federation.

01:51:09.000 --> 01:51:17.000
In this regard, countries that lend to the world market

01:51:18.000 --> 01:51:23.000
and at the same time take loans on the same world market,

01:51:23.000 --> 01:51:27.000
are interested in the coordination of their positions

01:51:27.000 --> 01:51:33.000
and in the development of common requirements and schemes for repaying loans.

01:51:33.000 --> 01:51:37.000
In this regard, the Paris Club stands out.

