02:15:04.000 --> 02:15:12.000
migration growth was replaced by only 3-4% of the natural population decline.

02:15:13.000 --> 02:15:19.000
In 2007, there was a sharp jump,

02:15:19.000 --> 02:15:23.000
and migration growth increased by 32%.

02:15:23.000 --> 02:15:30.000
This is due to the legal basis of regulation of the workforce.

02:15:30.000 --> 02:15:36.000
In particular, in 2003-2004, when, as you can see from the diagram,

02:15:37.000 --> 02:15:41.000
migration growth was minimal,

02:15:41.000 --> 02:15:46.000
at that time, the migration legislation was tightened,

02:15:46.000 --> 02:15:49.000
and the requirements for migrants were tightened,

02:15:49.000 --> 02:15:53.000
the requirements for employers were also expanded,

02:15:53.000 --> 02:15:58.000
because they had to pay the corresponding migration taxes.

02:15:58.000 --> 02:16:03.000
But in 2007, there was a sudden surge.

02:16:03.000 --> 02:16:08.000
In this case, we can consider this a statistical error.

02:16:08.000 --> 02:16:15.000
Why? Because finally, in 2007-2006,

02:16:15.000 --> 02:16:22.000
the requirements for foreign workers to be registered in the country were tightened.

02:16:22.000 --> 02:16:25.000
And due to purely administrative measures,

02:16:25.000 --> 02:16:30.000
those workers who had previously migrated to the country,

02:16:30.000 --> 02:16:33.000
but they were not considered migrants,

02:16:33.000 --> 02:16:35.000
we did not take them into account at all,

02:16:35.000 --> 02:16:37.000
they now appeared.

02:16:37.000 --> 02:16:41.000
Based on this, we get that there is indeed a 32% migration growth

02:16:41.000 --> 02:16:45.000
from countries of the Middle East.

02:16:48.000 --> 02:16:53.000
If we look at the statistics of 2007,

02:16:53.000 --> 02:16:59.000
in January-April, the number of migrants in Russia increased by 9.5%.

02:16:59.000 --> 02:17:07.000
Moreover, the external migration growth of the population increased by 50-40%.

02:17:07.000 --> 02:17:10.000
This confirms the words I said earlier,

02:17:10.000 --> 02:17:14.000
that our domestic migration is developing relatively steadily,

02:17:14.000 --> 02:17:20.000
and not at such a rapid pace as the external migration of the population.

02:17:21.000 --> 02:17:26.000
The number of immigrants decreased by 10.6%,

02:17:26.000 --> 02:17:32.000
and in the countries of the Far East, the number of migrants decreased by 17.4%.

02:17:32.000 --> 02:17:39.000
In general, these last data reflect the positive trend,

02:17:39.000 --> 02:17:45.000
which means that for certain layers of the population,

02:17:45.000 --> 02:17:53.000
the return to the country from abroad or the current work in the homeland

02:17:53.000 --> 02:18:00.000
is more attractive than leaving the country with all the problems and consequences.

02:18:00.000 --> 02:18:06.000
On the other hand, the reason for such a reduction in migration

02:18:06.000 --> 02:18:12.000
is the counter-intensification of the legislation of different countries.

02:18:13.000 --> 02:18:17.000
For example, the UK,

02:18:17.000 --> 02:18:23.000
which has joined the EU, Poland and the Baltic states,

02:18:23.000 --> 02:18:27.000
after the post-Soviet period,

02:18:27.000 --> 02:18:33.000
has now offered a large enough migration flow

02:18:33.000 --> 02:18:39.000
to more developed countries.

02:18:42.000 --> 02:18:46.000
This is beneficial for the income of Western European countries.

02:18:46.000 --> 02:18:51.000
Therefore, in order to balance the migration flow,

02:18:51.000 --> 02:18:56.000
Western European countries are tightening their legislation.

02:18:56.000 --> 02:19:03.000
In this regard, the number of permits for entry to Russia, the UK or Germany has decreased.

02:19:03.000 --> 02:19:11.000
As we can see, migration growth is not only related to the wishes of the people,

02:19:11.000 --> 02:19:16.000
but also to the reasons for their subjective position.

02:19:16.000 --> 02:19:21.000
Migration, including labor migration,

02:19:21.000 --> 02:19:28.000
is connected with a large number of factors of state regulation.

02:19:28.000 --> 02:19:34.000
The national government tries to balance the labor market

02:19:34.000 --> 02:19:40.000
and invite only those migrants who are desirable for the country's economic development.

02:19:41.000 --> 02:19:47.000
The reasons for labor migration can be divided into two main categories.

02:19:47.000 --> 02:19:50.000
These are economic reasons and other reasons.

02:19:50.000 --> 02:19:56.000
Economic reasons depend on the fluctuation of demand and supply of labor.

02:19:56.000 --> 02:19:59.000
Demand is inflated by the private and state sectors.

02:19:59.000 --> 02:20:04.000
It usually decreases due to the cyclical unemployment and decline in the economy.

02:20:04.000 --> 02:20:07.000
As we know, in modern Russia,

02:20:07.000 --> 02:20:10.000
the economic growth has been increasing for several years in a row.

02:20:10.000 --> 02:20:14.000
The GDP is about 6% of the GDP.

02:20:14.000 --> 02:20:22.000
The cyclical unemployment is decreasing and the number of jobs is increasing.

02:20:22.000 --> 02:20:26.000
This can be taken up by potential migrants.

02:20:26.000 --> 02:20:36.000
On the other hand, the demographic situation is another natural reason for the fluctuation in the supply of labor.

02:20:36.000 --> 02:20:44.000
As we know, not only Russia, or rather the main regions where these trends have appeared,

02:20:44.000 --> 02:20:46.000
are Western Europe.

02:20:46.000 --> 02:20:49.000
Russia is no exception here.

02:20:49.000 --> 02:20:51.000
It is the aging of the population.

02:20:51.000 --> 02:20:56.000
Based on the fact that the population is not actually increasing,

02:20:56.000 --> 02:20:58.000
but the population is declining,

02:20:59.000 --> 02:21:11.000
it certainly contributes to the government's idea of how to attract the lacking workforce to the country.

02:21:11.000 --> 02:21:19.000
The next reason for labor migration is the uneven accumulation of investment resources.

02:21:19.000 --> 02:21:25.000
This is due to domestic migration.

02:21:25.000 --> 02:21:30.000
Some regions can be more developed, others less developed in terms of economy.

02:21:30.000 --> 02:21:36.000
This is also due to the international structure of distribution of jobs

02:21:36.000 --> 02:21:41.000
due to the different levels of development of the economy of different countries

02:21:41.000 --> 02:21:45.000
and the different levels of development of both industry and the service sector.

02:21:45.000 --> 02:21:54.000
The next reason for labor migration is the emergence of structural unemployment in countries.

02:21:54.000 --> 02:21:56.000
What does this mean?

02:21:56.000 --> 02:22:00.000
Structural unemployment, I remind you, is due to the course of economic theory,

02:22:00.000 --> 02:22:04.000
is associated with the moral aging of a number of professions.

02:22:04.000 --> 02:22:10.000
Accordingly, those regions that are mainly oriented to some kind of activity,

02:22:10.000 --> 02:22:17.000
for example, mining, industry, and, accordingly, the production of cocaine, coal,

02:22:17.000 --> 02:22:27.000
are often in a state of a semi-congealed process in a number of countries and regions.

02:22:27.000 --> 02:22:34.000
As a result, there is an accumulation of excess workforce, which must find its application somewhere.

02:22:34.000 --> 02:22:38.000
This is the reason for both domestic and international labor migration.

02:22:38.000 --> 02:22:44.000
And the last, often the most important factor that contributes to the migration of the population

02:22:44.000 --> 02:22:47.000
is the difference in the level of labor payment between countries.

02:22:47.000 --> 02:22:55.000
Of course, this factor is associated with the inequality of the development of countries as such,

02:22:55.000 --> 02:23:01.000
but the only thing that can be said here, or rather, what should be noted,

02:23:01.000 --> 02:23:06.000
is that the same international trade, international investments, these processes,

02:23:06.000 --> 02:23:13.000
lead to the fact that the level of labor payment between countries is slowly leveling out.

02:23:13.000 --> 02:23:18.000
Based on this, of course, these processes are quite long,

02:23:18.000 --> 02:23:22.000
but based on this concept of leveling the level of labor payment,

02:23:22.000 --> 02:23:28.000
we can conclude that, probably, these processes can be somehow accelerated.

02:23:28.000 --> 02:23:34.000
Based on this, within the framework of the debates that take place in the World Trade Organization,

02:23:34.000 --> 02:23:40.000
developed countries propose to introduce certain international standards of labor payment

02:23:41.000 --> 02:23:45.000
to the export markets, to the export markets, to the export markets,

02:23:45.000 --> 02:23:51.000
proving that in this case, this is, let's say, a situation of low labor payment,

02:23:51.000 --> 02:23:56.000
this is a situation, let's say, artificially created in this country,

02:23:56.000 --> 02:24:00.000
and based on the fact that these countries receive quite high incomes,

02:24:00.000 --> 02:24:06.000
they could increase the labor payment at the state level, due to state decisions.

02:24:07.000 --> 02:24:12.000
Nevertheless, the difference in the level of labor payment is preserved,

02:24:12.000 --> 02:24:19.000
and this is, again, the reason for the inter-country movement of labor resources.

02:24:19.000 --> 02:24:26.000
Other non-economic reasons that may arise are, of course, political,

02:24:26.000 --> 02:24:30.000
migration of the population from areas associated with military actions,

02:24:31.000 --> 02:24:36.000
religious, ethnic, and other.

02:24:36.000 --> 02:24:39.000
But in this case, within the framework of the course,

02:24:39.000 --> 02:24:44.000
we are most interested in the reasons for economic migration,

02:24:44.000 --> 02:24:47.000
which we have stopped at.

02:24:47.000 --> 02:24:52.000
There are a number of factors that restrain labor migration.

02:24:52.000 --> 02:24:57.000
As you know, in Russia, there has been a heated debate recently

02:24:57.000 --> 02:25:01.000
about whether it is necessary to actively open borders

02:25:01.000 --> 02:25:06.000
and invite the labor force to our Russian labor market.

02:25:06.000 --> 02:25:13.000
The life standards that restrain this are, in this case,

02:25:13.000 --> 02:25:18.000
that is, as soon as an immigrant arrives in the country of his destination,

02:25:18.000 --> 02:25:24.000
in the country of his dream, it is assumed that he, as a citizen of the country,

02:25:24.000 --> 02:25:29.000
must be provided with the same social guarantees as all citizens,

02:25:29.000 --> 02:25:35.000
even during the transition period, until he has become a citizen,

02:25:35.000 --> 02:25:38.000
at least some minimum level of these life standards.

02:25:38.000 --> 02:25:40.000
And this is the country's cost.

02:25:40.000 --> 02:25:46.000
Accordingly, on the one hand, the state must develop programs

02:25:46.000 --> 02:25:51.000
to support such life standards for immigrants,

02:25:51.000 --> 02:25:54.000
in which the country is interested.

02:25:54.000 --> 02:25:59.000
And on the other hand, there is a contradiction here,

02:25:59.000 --> 02:26:03.000
due to the fact that certain financial resources need to be spent on this.

02:26:03.000 --> 02:26:08.000
Moreover, these financial resources are taken away from their, so to speak, native citizens,

02:26:08.000 --> 02:26:11.000
and are taken away, accordingly, from those programs

02:26:11.000 --> 02:26:17.000
that could create additional jobs for their citizens with a higher wage.

02:26:18.000 --> 02:26:22.000
The next restraining factor is the migration restrictions

02:26:22.000 --> 02:26:25.000
introduced by the government of one country or another.

02:26:25.000 --> 02:26:29.000
In particular, migration taxes.

02:26:29.000 --> 02:26:32.000
According to the legislation of many countries,

02:26:32.000 --> 02:26:37.000
employers are obliged to pay a certain tax for an invited immigrant.

02:26:37.000 --> 02:26:40.000
This is due to the fact that, most likely,

02:26:40.000 --> 02:26:46.000
the salary of this immigrant will be much lower than the standards

02:26:46.000 --> 02:26:48.000
that are already established in this country.

02:26:48.000 --> 02:26:50.000
There is another point here.

02:26:50.000 --> 02:26:55.000
In general, the minimum hourly wage is usually established in countries.

02:26:55.000 --> 02:26:58.000
And from the point of view of the law, you cannot pay less.

02:26:58.000 --> 02:27:03.000
Accordingly, those employers who are trying to officially register workers,

02:27:03.000 --> 02:27:06.000
in this case, they will go against the legislation.

02:27:06.000 --> 02:27:11.000
And therefore, there is a tendency of a shadow labor market,

02:27:11.000 --> 02:27:16.000
when they try, both in post-socialist countries and in developed countries,

02:27:16.000 --> 02:27:20.000
not to register migrants in order to have some opportunity

02:27:20.000 --> 02:27:25.000
to pay them a salary much lower than the standards

02:27:25.000 --> 02:27:31.000
that are associated with those specialties and with the level of payment

02:27:31.000 --> 02:27:34.000
that exist in the far-reaching national economy.

02:27:34.000 --> 02:27:39.000
Well, the last restraining factor is social, ethnic, religious problems.

02:27:39.000 --> 02:27:44.000
Again, in order to maintain social standards for this population of immigrants.

02:27:44.000 --> 02:27:50.000
On the one hand, this is important, because if you are invited to such a labor force,

02:27:50.000 --> 02:27:53.000
which will potentially create your GDP,

02:27:53.000 --> 02:27:58.000
to perform some activities that the indigenous population does not want to perform,

02:27:58.000 --> 02:28:01.000
then you must provide certain social guarantees.

02:28:01.000 --> 02:28:04.000
On the other hand, there are, of course, conflicts here,

02:28:04.000 --> 02:28:08.000
which are associated with ethnic and religious problems.

02:28:08.000 --> 02:28:14.000
And everyone has heard about the events that took place in France in 2006.

02:28:14.000 --> 02:28:20.000
Although it would seem that France adopted a very favorable political program

02:28:20.000 --> 02:28:30.000
to support migrants from Asian and African countries.

02:28:30.000 --> 02:28:33.000
What are the forms of migration of the labor force?

02:28:33.000 --> 02:28:35.000
The following forms are proposed.

02:28:35.000 --> 02:28:38.000
The first form is the current resettlement.

02:28:38.000 --> 02:28:41.000
It is usually associated with the fact that in one or another part of the Earth

02:28:41.000 --> 02:28:44.000
or in one or another part of some separate national economy,

02:28:44.000 --> 02:28:48.000
industrial complexes are created, integration processes take place,

02:28:48.000 --> 02:28:58.000
and such a surge in demand of the labor force stimulates the arrival of this labor force to this territory.

02:28:58.000 --> 02:29:02.000
The next form of migration is associated with the following reasons.

02:29:02.000 --> 02:29:05.000
The first reason is migration within the border zone.

02:29:05.000 --> 02:29:10.000
Of course, this form of migration is quite widespread.

02:29:10.000 --> 02:29:14.000
And here not only, for example, European countries can serve,

02:29:14.000 --> 02:29:21.000
but also Russia, when people go to work in neighboring countries in the border zones.

02:29:21.000 --> 02:29:26.000
Agricultural migration is mainly associated with the climate cycle,

02:29:26.000 --> 02:29:32.000
with the cycle of seasons, and then the arrival of agricultural workers.

02:29:32.000 --> 02:29:35.000
This is a normal practice that is developed,

02:29:35.000 --> 02:29:38.000
including in Western European countries,

02:29:38.000 --> 02:29:44.000
which offer to come to agricultural workers for a certain season.

02:29:44.000 --> 02:29:50.000
And in this regard, agricultural migration is closely intertwined with seasonal migration,

02:29:50.000 --> 02:29:54.000
when not only agricultural work, but also construction work takes place.

02:29:54.000 --> 02:29:58.000
We, again, in Russia, have such types of migration,

02:29:58.000 --> 02:30:07.000
when, for example, workers from Vietnam or China come to some of our agricultural companies

02:30:07.000 --> 02:30:13.000
for difficult work on growing, plowing, in general, cleaning vegetables.

02:30:13.000 --> 02:30:20.000
And seasonal migration for construction work is, in general, just in sight of all,

02:30:20.000 --> 02:30:23.000
for Moscow residents, for the residents of cities.

02:30:23.000 --> 02:30:29.000
This is exactly the area of labor offer, it works quite actively.

02:30:29.000 --> 02:30:36.000
And most importantly, the government of cities agrees to such migration.

02:30:36.000 --> 02:30:44.000
And the first thing that is established in the accommodation of people invited,

02:30:44.000 --> 02:30:48.000
as workers on the territory of a given region,

02:30:48.000 --> 02:30:54.000
is construction work, then transport, then cleaning the territory,

02:30:54.000 --> 02:31:01.000
various types of work that may not attract local residents.

02:31:01.000 --> 02:31:05.000
What is the geography of migration?

02:31:05.000 --> 02:31:10.000
Of course, the point of attraction of migrants will be developed countries,

02:31:10.000 --> 02:31:15.000
such as the United States, Canada, Australia, all of Western Europe, the Middle East.

02:31:15.000 --> 02:31:20.000
And developing countries, it would seem, should not be the point of attraction of migrants.

02:31:20.000 --> 02:31:23.000
But, given that recently a whole group of countries is developing,

02:31:23.000 --> 02:31:25.000
which is called new industrial countries,

02:31:25.000 --> 02:31:30.000
all the same countries, which have an export-oriented economy.

02:31:30.000 --> 02:31:36.000
These are the countries where the indigenous population gets the opportunity to get a higher salary,

02:31:36.000 --> 02:31:40.000
to move to these, so to speak, enclaves of industrial development.

02:31:40.000 --> 02:31:45.000
Of course, the level of income in these countries increases compared to another group of developing countries.

02:31:45.000 --> 02:31:49.000
And then migration occurs, in particular, for example, in Latin America,

02:31:49.000 --> 02:31:54.000
migration to more developed countries, Argentina and Mexico.

02:31:54.000 --> 02:31:58.000
New industrial countries are another point of attraction,

02:31:58.000 --> 02:32:04.000
South Korea, Malaysia, in this case, this is the same example,

02:32:04.000 --> 02:32:07.000
associated with export-oriented development.

02:32:07.000 --> 02:32:11.000
Migration sources, of course, are the whole block of developing countries,

02:32:11.000 --> 02:32:17.000
the main one of which is Asia, the Asian region.

02:32:17.000 --> 02:32:23.000
And the source of migration, of course, is the block of post-socialist countries,

02:32:23.000 --> 02:32:25.000
groups of post-socialist countries,

02:32:25.000 --> 02:32:32.000
because not in all of these countries the standard of living is high enough.

02:32:32.000 --> 02:32:35.000
And, first of all, qualified personnel migrate,

02:32:35.000 --> 02:32:39.000
and then these personnel, who are highly unemployed,

02:32:39.000 --> 02:32:44.000
could not find an application for their activities.

02:32:46.000 --> 02:32:52.000
In countries, when developing state programs,

02:32:52.000 --> 02:32:54.000
when developing legislative acts,

02:32:54.000 --> 02:33:02.000
first of all, a selective approach to immigrants is declared.

02:33:02.000 --> 02:33:07.000
First of all, workers are chosen to perform hard, harmful, unqualified work,

02:33:07.000 --> 02:33:09.000
certainly for low wages,

02:33:09.000 --> 02:33:11.000
but which are unlikely to be agreed upon,

02:33:11.000 --> 02:33:15.000
or to a lesser extent, their own personnel are agreed upon.

02:33:15.000 --> 02:33:19.000
Specialists for new and promising industries,

02:33:19.000 --> 02:33:22.000
this is the same import of brains,

02:33:22.000 --> 02:33:25.000
highly specialized engineers, bank servants,

02:33:25.000 --> 02:33:29.000
certainly those who migrate in this stream,

02:33:29.000 --> 02:33:34.000
they are interested in getting a more adequate living environment,

02:33:34.000 --> 02:33:38.000
a good place to work and high incomes.

02:33:38.000 --> 02:33:42.000
Also representatives of rare professions,

02:33:42.000 --> 02:33:46.000
such as diamond border guards or painting restorers,

02:33:46.000 --> 02:33:50.000
doctors, who are practicing some special methods of treatment.

02:33:50.000 --> 02:33:54.000
World-renowned specialists, musicians, artists, scientists,

02:33:54.000 --> 02:33:56.000
athletes, doctors, writers.

02:33:57.000 --> 02:34:04.000
In this case, it is impossible to say that this is a complete stream of immigrants

02:34:04.000 --> 02:34:08.000
associated with some economic preferences.

02:34:08.000 --> 02:34:13.000
Why? Because often specialists with a world-renowned name

02:34:13.000 --> 02:34:17.000
are, as they call themselves, citizens of the world.

02:34:17.000 --> 02:34:21.000
And for them, territorial migration is a natural process,

02:34:21.000 --> 02:34:26.000
they bring their works to different territories,

02:34:26.000 --> 02:34:31.000
in different languages, for different consumers.

02:34:31.000 --> 02:34:35.000
The next group is large businessmen,

02:34:35.000 --> 02:34:39.000
who invest and create new jobs.

02:34:39.000 --> 02:34:42.000
And many countries have a program

02:34:42.000 --> 02:34:46.000
that offers to get a kind of residence,

02:34:46.000 --> 02:34:50.000
if you invest certain investment funds in this country,

02:34:50.000 --> 02:34:55.000
then this program is not aimed at creating a job market,

02:34:55.000 --> 02:35:00.000
but at stimulating investment in this region.

02:35:00.000 --> 02:35:05.000
The next aspect that we need to consider

02:35:05.000 --> 02:35:10.000
is a special kind of international economic relations,

02:35:10.000 --> 02:35:14.000
such as integration.

02:35:14.000 --> 02:35:18.000
What are the main features of integration?

02:35:18.000 --> 02:35:21.000
In principle, the processes of interconnection,

02:35:21.000 --> 02:35:24.000
the establishment of some economic relations,

02:35:24.000 --> 02:35:29.000
were characteristic of different eras and stages of economic development

02:35:29.000 --> 02:35:32.000
of countries in the market economy.

02:35:32.000 --> 02:35:35.000
But integration is a special stage,

02:35:35.000 --> 02:35:38.000
it has some special features.

02:35:38.000 --> 02:35:41.000
And the first specific feature

02:35:41.000 --> 02:35:45.000
that distinguishes integration from other processes of interaction

02:35:45.000 --> 02:35:49.000
is the interstate regulation of national economies.

02:35:49.000 --> 02:35:53.000
The next feature of international integration

02:35:53.000 --> 02:35:58.000
is the formation of a regional economic complex.

02:35:58.000 --> 02:36:01.000
Countries agree that they will have some economic zones

02:36:01.000 --> 02:36:06.000
and, accordingly, more close cooperation relations in this territory.

02:36:06.000 --> 02:36:10.000
Based on this, national barriers are eliminated,

02:36:10.000 --> 02:36:13.000
not only in relation to the movement of goods and services,

02:36:13.000 --> 02:36:17.000
but also in relation to the movement of labor and capital.

02:36:17.000 --> 02:36:21.000
Accordingly, as a result of such a rapid integration process,

02:36:21.000 --> 02:36:24.000
a kind of a single regional market should be created.

02:36:24.000 --> 02:36:28.000
And such redistribution,

02:36:28.000 --> 02:36:32.000
an adequate principle of efficiency of redistribution of all resources

02:36:32.000 --> 02:36:35.000
on this integration territory

02:36:35.000 --> 02:36:38.000
should provide such a synergetic effect,

02:36:38.000 --> 02:36:42.000
the effect of growth, productivity, labor and standard of living.

02:36:42.000 --> 02:36:45.000
What are the forms of integration?

02:36:45.000 --> 02:36:50.000
Basically, the forms of integration are connected with the stages

02:36:50.000 --> 02:36:55.000
of integration in one or another territory.

02:36:55.000 --> 02:37:00.000
And depending on the emergence of new integration agreements,

02:37:00.000 --> 02:37:05.000
these forms of integration develop

02:37:05.000 --> 02:37:11.000
and give the opportunity to develop the regional territories,

02:37:11.000 --> 02:37:13.000
the regional economy.

02:37:13.000 --> 02:37:16.000
First of all, preferential trade agreements.

02:37:16.000 --> 02:37:21.000
This is the first stage of the conclusion of foreign trade relations.

02:37:21.000 --> 02:37:26.000
It is assumed that the tariffs are preserved here,

02:37:26.000 --> 02:37:30.000
the entire range of national tariffs and other restrictions

02:37:30.000 --> 02:37:32.000
in relation to the third countries.

02:37:32.000 --> 02:37:35.000
But in relation to the countries that have entered

02:37:35.000 --> 02:37:38.000
into this preferential trade agreement,

02:37:38.000 --> 02:37:43.000
it is assumed that the movement of goods will be free of any barriers.

02:37:43.000 --> 02:37:47.000
The next level of integration and the next form, respectively,

02:37:47.000 --> 02:37:50.000
is the free trade zone.

02:37:50.000 --> 02:37:55.000
It is assumed that all barriers in mutual trade are completely abolished here.

02:37:55.000 --> 02:37:57.000
Customs union.

02:37:57.000 --> 02:38:01.000
Moreover, when a free trade zone is created,

02:38:01.000 --> 02:38:03.000
I want to draw your attention to the fact that

02:38:03.000 --> 02:38:05.000
not only the movement of goods and services is assumed here,

02:38:05.000 --> 02:38:09.000
but also the free movement of factors of production, capital,

02:38:09.000 --> 02:38:11.000
the very working force, migration of the population.

02:38:11.000 --> 02:38:13.000
Customs union.

02:38:13.000 --> 02:38:16.000
It is assumed that the trust and relations between countries

02:38:16.000 --> 02:38:18.000
have already reached such a level

02:38:18.000 --> 02:38:26.000
that they not only refuse some barriers in mutual relations and mutual trade,

02:38:26.000 --> 02:38:30.000
but at this stage they even produce a single tariff,

02:38:30.000 --> 02:38:34.000
a single measure limiting or, so to speak,

02:38:34.000 --> 02:38:39.000
on the contrary, allowing importation to its integrated territory.

02:38:39.000 --> 02:38:42.000
That is, a single tariff in relation to outsiders.

02:38:42.000 --> 02:38:45.000
The last principle is the common market.

02:38:45.000 --> 02:38:49.000
Here, the freedom of movement of factors of production,

02:38:49.000 --> 02:38:52.000
while assuming that all the previous stages,

02:38:52.000 --> 02:38:53.000
which I have already mentioned,

02:38:53.000 --> 02:38:57.000
are included as components of the concept of the common market.

02:38:57.000 --> 02:38:59.000
Economic union.

02:38:59.000 --> 02:39:05.000
This is the highest level of integration development.

02:39:05.000 --> 02:39:07.000
Such an integration group is created.

02:39:07.000 --> 02:39:11.000
The main feature of this integration group

02:39:11.000 --> 02:39:14.000
is that not only do certain committees

02:39:14.000 --> 02:39:17.000
on the regulation of relations be created here,

02:39:17.000 --> 02:39:21.000
but here, so to speak, a supranational government is created.

02:39:21.000 --> 02:39:25.000
An example of such an economic union is the European Union.

02:39:25.000 --> 02:39:30.000
We all know that it has its own European Parliament

02:39:30.000 --> 02:39:32.000
and, accordingly, its own European Government.

02:39:32.000 --> 02:39:36.000
Based on this, the level of integration here is not only related to economic,

02:39:36.000 --> 02:39:38.000
but also to political integration.

02:39:38.000 --> 02:39:41.000
Of course, the economic union becomes more complete

02:39:41.000 --> 02:39:45.000
when a single currency policy is carried out

02:39:45.000 --> 02:39:48.000
and such a single currency zone is created.

02:39:48.000 --> 02:39:52.000
What are the main two effects of integration?

02:39:52.000 --> 02:39:57.000
The first effect is the creation of trade or the trade-based effect.

02:39:57.000 --> 02:40:00.000
It is assumed that within the customs union,

02:40:00.000 --> 02:40:07.000
there is a situation that there are countries

02:40:07.000 --> 02:40:12.000
whose production costs are much lower than in the countries of outsiders

02:40:12.000 --> 02:40:15.000
who have not joined this trade union.

02:40:15.000 --> 02:40:18.000
Thus, the countries of the union member

02:40:18.000 --> 02:40:28.000
are not able to supply their products to the union members.

02:40:28.000 --> 02:40:33.000
And, accordingly, since they are no longer divided by customs barriers,

02:40:33.000 --> 02:40:38.000
it becomes possible for such a manufacturer

02:40:38.000 --> 02:40:43.000
to distribute resources more efficiently and rationally

02:40:43.000 --> 02:40:47.000
and to produce goods for the entire integration union.

02:40:47.000 --> 02:40:49.000
The second effect is the rejection of trade.

02:40:49.000 --> 02:40:51.000
This is a negative effect of integration.

02:40:51.000 --> 02:40:54.000
It is usually due to the fact that outside the union,

02:40:54.000 --> 02:40:58.000
there is a manufacturer whose costs are lower

02:40:58.000 --> 02:41:00.000
and the production is more rationally organized

02:41:00.000 --> 02:41:04.000
and the quality of the product is higher.

02:41:04.000 --> 02:41:09.000
But these integration tariffs begin to apply against it.

02:41:09.000 --> 02:41:12.000
And then all the countries of the integration union

02:41:12.000 --> 02:41:16.000
are forced to refuse to supply imports,

02:41:16.000 --> 02:41:20.000
although it would seem that the country of outsiders

02:41:20.000 --> 02:41:23.000
clearly has some economic advantages over its products.

02:41:23.000 --> 02:41:27.000
And then they are forced to switch to the consumption and demand

02:41:27.000 --> 02:41:31.000
of those goods that are on the territory of the trade union.

02:41:31.000 --> 02:41:34.000
Therefore, this effect is called a trade distraction.

02:41:34.000 --> 02:41:37.000
In principle, the scale of such trade can be reduced,

02:41:37.000 --> 02:41:40.000
because, of course, by some parameters,

02:41:40.000 --> 02:41:44.000
this product is less high-quality or more expensive,

02:41:44.000 --> 02:41:48.000
and, in general, it does not satisfy the consumer.

02:41:48.000 --> 02:41:51.000
What are the examples of integration unions?

02:41:51.000 --> 02:41:54.000
In principle, there are quite a lot of them.

02:41:54.000 --> 02:41:57.000
It would be possible to list them by regions.

02:41:57.000 --> 02:41:59.000
In Africa, there are their own unions,

02:41:59.000 --> 02:42:01.000
in America, there are their own unions.

02:42:01.000 --> 02:42:04.000
In each region, on the territory of each continent,

02:42:04.000 --> 02:42:07.000
there is some kind of integration union,

02:42:07.000 --> 02:42:10.000
because countries understand the advantages of integration,

02:42:10.000 --> 02:42:12.000
which we have already talked about.

02:42:12.000 --> 02:42:15.000
This is, in general, an opportunity to increase trade,

02:42:15.000 --> 02:42:18.000
an opportunity for some kind of integration,

02:42:18.000 --> 02:42:20.000
cooperation solutions,

02:42:20.000 --> 02:42:23.000
to develop, for example, the same technology transfer,

02:42:23.000 --> 02:42:26.000
or to equip their workforce on the territory of another country,

02:42:26.000 --> 02:42:29.000
excess workforce, and so on.

02:42:29.000 --> 02:42:33.000
So, the most, so to speak, stable integration group,

02:42:33.000 --> 02:42:35.000
which has achieved the highest results

02:42:35.000 --> 02:42:37.000
among the world countries so far,

02:42:37.000 --> 02:42:39.000
is the European Economic Community,

02:42:39.000 --> 02:42:46.000
which in 1992 already included 15 countries of the world,

02:42:46.000 --> 02:42:52.000
and gradually included countries of the post-Soviet space.

02:42:52.000 --> 02:42:56.000
But now the countries of the European Union are tasked with the fact

02:42:56.000 --> 02:43:01.000
that they no longer want to further expand the European Union

02:43:01.000 --> 02:43:05.000
and include all those who wish to leave the European territories,

02:43:05.000 --> 02:43:07.000
the post-Soviet space,

02:43:07.000 --> 02:43:11.000
precisely because there are some standards of living standards,

02:43:11.000 --> 02:43:13.000
social guarantees,

02:43:13.000 --> 02:43:15.000
which are guaranteed to all members,

02:43:15.000 --> 02:43:23.000
to all people who live on the territory of the European Economic Community.

02:43:23.000 --> 02:43:27.000
And, accordingly, this requires budgetary flows,

02:43:27.000 --> 02:43:30.000
and, in particular, redistribution of budgetary funds,

02:43:30.000 --> 02:43:33.000
the funds of the General Budget Congress of the European Union

02:43:33.000 --> 02:43:37.000
in favor of such more backward economies.

02:43:37.000 --> 02:43:41.000
And since they already had experience of working with more backward economies,

02:43:41.000 --> 02:43:45.000
take the territory of Portugal, Greece,

02:43:45.000 --> 02:43:52.000
accordingly, these territories are in general debtors to the rest of the EU members,

02:43:52.000 --> 02:43:54.000
they have their own problems.

02:43:54.000 --> 02:43:59.000
Then, in general, to accumulate more problems for the EU economy

02:43:59.000 --> 02:44:05.000
and, of course, the government of these countries does not want to include the EU members yet.

02:44:05.000 --> 02:44:12.000
They want these countries to achieve some acceptable level of development on their own,

02:44:12.000 --> 02:44:16.000
so that they join the EU as equal members, not as donor countries.

02:44:16.000 --> 02:44:24.000
The next well-developed form of integration is the Association of States of Southeast Asia,

02:44:24.000 --> 02:44:26.000
or ASEAN.

02:44:26.000 --> 02:44:28.000
Ten countries are included.

02:44:28.000 --> 02:44:32.000
The main distinguishing feature of this group of countries

02:44:32.000 --> 02:44:41.000
is that this is an integration alliance based on the principles of openness.

02:44:41.000 --> 02:44:45.000
That is, everyone who wants to enter the countries of East Asia

02:44:45.000 --> 02:44:48.000
and recognizes the principles of ASEAN,

02:44:48.000 --> 02:44:53.000
supports the implementation of the goals and objectives of this integration group,

02:44:53.000 --> 02:44:56.000
they can join this integration alliance.

02:44:56.000 --> 02:45:01.000
That is, it does not have such a rigid, closed type.

02:45:01.000 --> 02:45:12.000
As you can see, the countries of the first and second waves of industrialization

02:45:12.000 --> 02:45:14.000
are included in this integration alliance,

02:45:14.000 --> 02:45:17.000
these are Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand.

02:45:17.000 --> 02:45:24.000
Of course, there are also groups of less developed countries,

02:45:24.000 --> 02:45:26.000
such as Vietnam and Cambodia,

02:45:26.000 --> 02:45:37.000
but nevertheless, the trend here is that stronger countries help less developed countries to develop.

02:45:37.000 --> 02:45:42.000
Mercosur is a common market of countries of the South-Eastern Cone,

02:45:42.000 --> 02:45:46.000
created in 1991, Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay.

02:45:46.000 --> 02:45:54.000
In general, the countries are quite territorially close to each other,

02:45:54.000 --> 02:45:58.000
and, accordingly, they have traditional integration ties.

02:45:58.000 --> 02:46:04.000
The next example is NAFTA, the North American Association of Free Trade.

02:46:04.000 --> 02:46:09.000
In this case, the North American Association includes, in addition to the United States, Canada and Mexico.

02:46:09.000 --> 02:46:12.000
It was organized in 1992.

02:46:12.000 --> 02:46:17.000
This is the version of the integration alliance,

02:46:17.000 --> 02:46:22.000
when quite developed countries are included.

02:46:22.000 --> 02:46:25.000
Even Mexico, although it is a developing country,

02:46:25.000 --> 02:46:31.000
its level of development is not the lowest compared to other developing countries.

02:46:31.000 --> 02:46:35.000
Industrial integration and cooperation are developing here,

02:46:35.000 --> 02:46:45.000
and the pace and level of international trade between these countries is quite high.

02:46:45.000 --> 02:46:48.000
The CIS is the Association of Independent States.

02:46:48.000 --> 02:46:51.000
It was founded in 1991,

02:46:51.000 --> 02:46:56.000
and one of the sovereign states of the post-Soviet space was included here.

02:46:56.000 --> 02:46:59.000
Some of them, however, have already entered as observers.

02:46:59.000 --> 02:47:11.000
The CIS aims to restore the broken ties that were once quite closely developed within the Soviet Union,

02:47:11.000 --> 02:47:16.000
and to restore the economic and effective ties between these countries,

02:47:16.000 --> 02:47:18.000
because these are neighboring countries,

02:47:18.000 --> 02:47:25.000
and these are countries that are traditionally used to supplying goods to their territories,

02:47:25.000 --> 02:47:28.000
and are associated with historical traditions.

02:47:28.000 --> 02:47:34.000
The Eurasian Union is the new integration alliance.

02:47:34.000 --> 02:47:37.000
Russia pays special attention to it,

02:47:37.000 --> 02:47:45.000
and participates in various summits of this union.

02:47:45.000 --> 02:47:49.000
It was created on October 10, 2000.

02:47:49.000 --> 02:47:51.000
The recipients are the Customs Unions.

02:47:52.000 --> 02:47:57.000
It is assumed that within the Customs Union, tariffs are no longer accepted between countries.

02:47:57.000 --> 02:48:03.000
Now there is a process of producing a single tariff for the CIS,

02:48:03.000 --> 02:48:08.000
the issue of the currency and financial field is regulated,

02:48:08.000 --> 02:48:12.000
and the trade procedures are simplified.

02:48:12.000 --> 02:48:20.000
As you can see, the Eurasian countries are really included here,

02:48:20.000 --> 02:48:25.000
and Russia is certainly interested in joining this union,

02:48:25.000 --> 02:48:33.000
because it is assumed that these countries can simultaneously join other unions.

02:48:33.000 --> 02:48:38.000
Moreover, the Eurasian Union will be a balancing structure,

02:48:38.000 --> 02:48:45.000
which will take into account the mutual interests of the territorial position of these countries.

02:48:46.000 --> 02:48:51.000
The next feature and the next group of international relations

02:48:51.000 --> 02:48:56.000
is associated with the existence and emergence of transnational corporations,

02:48:56.000 --> 02:48:58.000
another term is transnationalization.

02:48:58.000 --> 02:49:05.000
In principle, a transnational international corporation is a large company

02:49:05.000 --> 02:49:09.000
that traditionally owns capital of one country.

02:49:09.000 --> 02:49:15.000
Of course, it can sell its shares or bonds on the open market,

02:49:15.000 --> 02:49:23.000
and then international capital enters this national capital according to the sources of the organization.

02:49:23.000 --> 02:49:28.000
Nevertheless, it usually has its headquarters in an apartment in some developed country,

02:49:28.000 --> 02:49:32.000
is attached to it by economic and political bonds.

02:49:32.000 --> 02:49:39.000
Transnational corporations exist at the current stage in both developed and developing countries.

02:49:39.000 --> 02:49:48.000
Multinational corporations are usually different from transnational corporations

02:49:48.000 --> 02:49:54.000
not in the business system, but in the fact that the capital that lies at its base

02:49:54.000 --> 02:49:58.000
usually belongs to the owners of a number of countries.

02:49:58.000 --> 02:50:04.000
And the branches of both transnational corporations are located in both developed and developing countries.

02:50:04.000 --> 02:50:09.000
The form of transnational corporations in Russia, from the point of view of legislation,

02:50:09.000 --> 02:50:14.000
is financial and industrial groups, such as Gazprom.

02:50:14.000 --> 02:50:20.000
Russian transnational corporations often do not register themselves as a financial and industrial group,

02:50:20.000 --> 02:50:31.000
which is associated with certain contradictions with the legislation that regulates the activities of financial and industrial groups.

02:50:31.000 --> 02:50:39.000
Nevertheless, this form of development of large companies is beneficial to any state,

02:50:39.000 --> 02:50:43.000
because it develops its branch network.

02:50:43.000 --> 02:50:52.000
This corporation represents the interests of the state abroad, creates a positive image of the state, and so on.

02:50:52.000 --> 02:50:56.000
Therefore, all countries in the world support their transnational corporations.

02:50:56.000 --> 02:51:02.000
Well, if you remember that often transnational corporations, based on their huge business,

02:51:02.000 --> 02:51:06.000
are also a major supplier of taxes to the budget of countries,

02:51:06.000 --> 02:51:15.000
then it is even more clear why national governments support their transnational corporations

02:51:15.000 --> 02:51:23.000
and try to lobby the interests of these transnational corporations.

02:51:23.000 --> 02:51:28.000
The volume of transnational corporations in the world is quite large.

02:51:28.000 --> 02:51:35.000
And the figures that you see on the slide now, they practically do not change for about 20 years.

02:51:35.000 --> 02:51:42.000
Indeed, they control about two-thirds of the world's trade, half of industrial production.

02:51:42.000 --> 02:51:48.000
About 10% of all employees work in industrial and household production.

02:51:48.000 --> 02:51:53.000
60% of the work is in mother companies, 40% in subsidiaries.

02:51:53.000 --> 02:52:01.000
They control 80% of existing patents and licenses in the world, know-how.

02:52:01.000 --> 02:52:10.000
These are powerful structures, not only qualified by the workforce, but also advanced technologies.

02:52:10.000 --> 02:52:19.000
They can have not only some industrial enterprises, but also scientific and research institutes.

02:52:19.000 --> 02:52:28.000
Almost 90% of direct foreign investments also go within the framework of transnational corporations,

02:52:28.000 --> 02:52:34.000
which, as I have said many times, are trying to overcome national trade barriers,

02:52:34.000 --> 02:52:41.000
organizing direct assembly production or production of some components in one country or another.

02:52:41.000 --> 02:52:51.000
Almost all raw materials trading, up to 90% of global trade, also refers to the activities of transnational corporations.

02:52:51.000 --> 02:52:59.000
I read that the raw material of some countries is compared with the raw material of transnational corporations.

02:52:59.000 --> 02:53:03.000
Let's not go into the problem of calculations.

02:53:03.000 --> 02:53:07.000
From the point of view of statistics, this is an incorrect comparison, because these are different levels of indicators.

02:53:07.000 --> 02:53:14.000
Nevertheless, we can imagine a sufficient list of these transnational corporations,

02:53:14.000 --> 02:53:21.000
whose output is more than the output of a number of stable and developed economies.

02:53:21.000 --> 02:53:24.000
Look at the rate of growth of the GDP.

02:53:24.000 --> 02:53:29.000
Despite the fact that the latest data is not provided in this scheme,

02:53:29.000 --> 02:53:33.000
it is clear that the rate of growth of the GDP is constantly increasing.

02:53:33.000 --> 02:53:42.000
This is a natural economic process of concentration and centralization of capital and development of capital in this direction.

02:53:42.000 --> 02:53:49.000
Transnational corporations allow to accumulate economic resources and redistribute them more rationally and effectively.

02:53:49.000 --> 02:53:55.000
If in 1939 there were only 30 TNK, and in 1970 there were 7000,

02:53:55.000 --> 02:54:03.000
by 2004 there were already 64000 TNK, and 830000 branches.

02:54:04.000 --> 02:54:14.000
As we can see, within these 830000 branches, contract relations, integrated cooperation, integration relations, are supported.

02:54:14.000 --> 02:54:20.000
And, accordingly, on the basis of these relations, it is possible to apply modern technologies,

02:54:20.000 --> 02:54:26.000
in particular, various technologies based on the Internet,

02:54:26.000 --> 02:54:32.000
to apply various computer programs for business management,

02:54:32.000 --> 02:54:39.000
and track, for example, the same goods flows, production flow from raw materials to the creation of ready-made products,

02:54:39.000 --> 02:54:44.000
and even its implementation within such a transnational corporation in an online mode.

02:54:44.000 --> 02:54:51.000
That is, having powerful resources, such firms certainly promote technical progress

02:54:51.000 --> 02:54:56.000
and create a positive charge for the economic development of all countries of the world.

02:54:56.000 --> 02:55:04.000
But, on the other hand, of course, transnational corporations can probably list a whole list of negative factors,

02:55:04.000 --> 02:55:06.000
precisely because they are monopolies.

02:55:06.000 --> 02:55:10.000
And like any monopoly, transnational corporations, even if it is not the only one in this industry,

02:55:10.000 --> 02:55:14.000
not the only, so to speak, oligopoly, there may be a dozen of them,

02:55:14.000 --> 02:55:22.000
but still, transnational corporations can use some monopoly approaches in the price of education,

02:55:22.000 --> 02:55:30.000
and then the prices for their products will be much higher than they could be in the case of a perfect competition or monopolistic competition.

02:55:30.000 --> 02:55:42.000
And another negative factor of the TNK, as a monopoly, is that if a transnational corporation has already invested some funds in some programs,

02:55:42.000 --> 02:55:50.000
and suddenly, God forbid, a parallel program has developed, then, in principle, it has the financial power to buy this program of activity,

02:55:50.000 --> 02:55:54.000
the program of creating a new product and put it on hold until the time comes.

02:55:54.000 --> 02:55:59.000
Because for it, in this case, it is not the principle of universal human efficiency that is important,

02:55:59.000 --> 02:56:04.000
but the principle of obtaining maximum profit from existing developments,

02:56:04.000 --> 02:56:10.000
which, of course, were funded by large funds that this transnational corporation carried out.

02:56:10.000 --> 02:56:17.000
And we should not go far, so to speak, for example, let's say, the same Microsoft with its programs,

02:56:17.000 --> 02:56:27.000
although against these manufacturers, so to speak, consumers constantly arise and try to initiate some processes,

02:56:27.000 --> 02:56:33.000
divide some pieces of this grandiose company, but nevertheless, the monopoly exists here,

02:56:34.000 --> 02:56:41.000
and the process with the negative effects of the existence of this monopoly is also developing.

02:56:41.000 --> 02:56:47.000
If we look at some more data on transnational corporations,

02:56:47.000 --> 02:56:55.000
then in 2005 there were already 65 thousand TNKs controlling 850 thousand branches,

02:56:55.000 --> 02:57:01.000
and there were 74 million people employed in these branches.

02:57:01.000 --> 02:57:08.000
In the territory of industrial developed countries, there were more than 80% of mother companies,

02:57:08.000 --> 02:57:13.000
but, as you can see, 20% were already in the territory of developing countries,

02:57:13.000 --> 02:57:17.000
33% were affiliated companies.

02:57:17.000 --> 02:57:24.000
In developing countries, respectively, about 20% and about 50%.

02:57:24.000 --> 02:57:32.000
In former socialist states, again, about half a percent of mother companies

02:57:32.000 --> 02:57:36.000
and 17% affiliated companies are associated with it.

02:57:36.000 --> 02:57:44.000
The next feature that is associated with transnationalization is the organization of banks.

02:57:44.000 --> 02:57:52.000
In principle, the division into transnational banks or industrial corporations in the modern economy is quite conditional.

02:57:52.000 --> 02:58:01.000
Why? Because the organizational structure of a transnational corporation is such that it is a diversified corporation,

02:58:01.000 --> 02:58:09.000
headed by a holding company, which simply holds a package of shares of various types of companies, enterprises,

02:58:09.000 --> 02:58:12.000
which are related to various types of activities.

02:58:12.000 --> 02:58:21.000
Therefore, a bank or an industrial corporation can be included in a modern transnational bank,

02:58:21.000 --> 02:58:27.000
and industrial structures, raw materials structures, trading structures, and so on.

02:58:27.000 --> 02:58:33.000
Based on this, there is enough division into transnational corporations, banks and industries.

02:58:33.000 --> 02:58:38.000
Not a single bank corporation is on the side of industrial production,

02:58:38.000 --> 02:58:49.000
it is closely associated with some financial structures, and, accordingly, with industrial structures,

02:58:49.000 --> 02:58:56.000
and an industrial transnational corporation simply contains specialized banks in itself.

02:58:56.000 --> 02:58:58.000
It is very closely associated with banking structures.

02:58:58.000 --> 02:59:05.000
Therefore, the idea that the main clients of banks are industrial and trading TNK

02:59:05.000 --> 02:59:13.000
is simply associated with the fact that the process of creating such giants, transnational corporations of the holding type,

02:59:13.000 --> 02:59:23.000
is certainly assumed that at some stage of development, these companies could be called primarily trading or industrial.

02:59:23.000 --> 02:59:31.000
In general, their development, of course, goes in the direction of globalization and the creation of such production-trading financial giants.

02:59:31.000 --> 02:59:37.000
The next feature of international economic relations is interstate regulation.

02:59:38.000 --> 02:59:46.000
It is assumed that this is not a form of creating a certain international government,

02:59:46.000 --> 02:59:52.000
although at other times, in publications, in journalistic articles, they even call it a world government.

02:59:52.000 --> 02:59:57.000
So far, at the modern level of economic development and political development,

02:59:57.000 --> 03:00:06.000
we can only say that such groups are created, which imply permanent meetings,

03:00:06.000 --> 03:00:14.000
agreements on permanent meetings of finance ministers, trade ministers, economy, heads of state governments.

03:00:14.000 --> 03:00:22.000
In this case, this is an option of such interstate structures,

03:00:22.000 --> 03:00:27.000
such as the organization of summits at the level of the Big Seven,

03:00:27.000 --> 03:00:32.000
where the seven most developed countries are included,

03:00:32.000 --> 03:00:39.000
in particular, the United States, Japan, France, England, Canada and Italy.

03:00:39.000 --> 03:00:47.000
And recently, due to the fact that Russia is not only a world's raw material treasure,

03:00:47.000 --> 03:00:57.000
but also a global economy itself, it is included in this meeting process.

03:00:57.000 --> 03:01:01.000
And now there are already summits of the Big Eight.

03:01:01.000 --> 03:01:07.000
Within the framework of these integration interstate meetings,

03:01:07.000 --> 03:01:14.000
the principles of a certain general financial strategy, foreign trade in development,

03:01:14.000 --> 03:01:19.000
the attitude to various global economic and non-economic global processes,

03:01:19.000 --> 03:01:22.000
in particular, the protection of the environment, are already being discussed.

03:01:22.000 --> 03:01:30.000
Another form of such interstate regulation, of course, is the state bodies,

03:01:30.000 --> 03:01:33.000
which exist within the framework of the integration group,

03:01:33.000 --> 03:01:38.000
which I have already mentioned, for example, within the framework of the Union, the European Union,

03:01:38.000 --> 03:01:44.000
their elected bodies and the government of the European Union.

03:01:44.000 --> 03:01:53.000
Another direction for the development of such negotiations, international relations,

03:01:53.000 --> 03:01:56.000
is the international organization,

03:01:56.000 --> 03:02:02.000
whose goal is to help develop international economic relations.

03:02:02.000 --> 03:02:09.000
And here the oldest structure is the International Monetary Fund,

03:02:09.000 --> 03:02:14.000
which was created by the Bretton Woods Conference in 1944,

03:02:14.000 --> 03:02:17.000
and was finally created in 1945.

03:02:17.000 --> 03:02:23.000
It was a result of the fact that the United States of America

03:02:23.000 --> 03:02:30.000
carried out a fairly extensive investment program to restore Europe.

03:02:30.000 --> 03:02:33.000
As you know, the Marshall Plan,

03:02:33.000 --> 03:02:40.000
and, of course, certain connections were developed to coordinate relations

03:02:40.000 --> 03:02:43.000
not only between the United States and some individual countries,

03:02:43.000 --> 03:02:48.000
but within the framework of all countries that are part of this regional impact.

03:02:48.000 --> 03:02:51.000
Therefore, in the end, the International Monetary Fund

03:02:51.000 --> 03:02:58.000
has become a fairly active structure that tries to influence international economic relations.

03:02:58.000 --> 03:03:03.000
Further, the membership of the IMF assumes that, in the end,

03:03:03.000 --> 03:03:10.000
these member states become members of the World Bank.

03:03:10.000 --> 03:03:13.000
And if we take Russia,

03:03:13.000 --> 03:03:18.000
it has become a member of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank since 1992.

03:03:18.000 --> 03:03:24.000
The main goal of the International Monetary Fund, of course, is social and economic.

03:03:24.000 --> 03:03:31.000
It is assumed that the IMF should not allow such problems as financial crises,

03:03:31.000 --> 03:03:35.000
help in the counteraction of economic crises as a whole,

03:03:35.000 --> 03:03:41.000
and, in general, the main goal is to balance economic relations between countries

03:03:41.000 --> 03:03:44.000
so that the interests of one country are not hampered

03:03:44.000 --> 03:03:49.000
and are not the cause of the development,

03:03:49.000 --> 03:03:53.000
as a result of the spiral of the global economic, financial and structural crisis.

03:03:53.000 --> 03:03:59.000
The next international organization is the General Trade Tariff Agreement,

03:03:59.000 --> 03:04:05.000
which was transformed into a world trade organization in 1995.

03:04:05.000 --> 03:04:11.000
This structure, the General Trade Tariff Agreement,

03:04:11.000 --> 03:04:16.000
allowed countries in Europe, first of all, the United States and Japan,

03:04:16.000 --> 03:04:22.000
to abandon the huge, almost prohibitive barriers

03:04:22.000 --> 03:04:30.000
that were fenced by the national economy of Europe and a number of developed countries of the world.

03:04:30.000 --> 03:04:37.000
Gradually, due to bilateral consultations and agreements between countries and members,

03:04:37.000 --> 03:04:42.000
the need to reduce all trade restrictions was realized.

03:04:42.000 --> 03:04:46.000
When the World Trade Organization was created in 1995,

03:04:46.000 --> 03:04:50.000
its goals were expanded, because they already concerned the reduction of barriers

03:04:50.000 --> 03:04:59.000
for international finance, for international transfer of technology and other economic relations.

03:05:00.000 --> 03:05:09.000
Thus, at the current stage, the World Trade Organization already includes 150 countries of the world.

03:05:09.000 --> 03:05:14.000
In particular, Russia is preparing for this entry,

03:05:14.000 --> 03:05:20.000
and has held bilateral and multilateral negotiations for decades

03:05:20.000 --> 03:05:26.000
to resolve all the issues that arise among the country's counter-agents,

03:05:26.000 --> 03:05:31.000
which are included in international economic relations in the world.

03:05:31.000 --> 03:05:35.000
And you understand, if there are 150 countries of the world,

03:05:35.000 --> 03:05:39.000
it was necessary to hold negotiations with 150 countries,

03:05:39.000 --> 03:05:45.000
to resolve all the issues and problems that existed.

03:05:45.000 --> 03:05:51.000
The last issue related to the development of international economic relations

03:05:51.000 --> 03:05:55.000
is another form, that is, the international transfer of technology.

03:05:55.000 --> 03:05:58.000
This includes licensed and patent relations,

03:05:58.000 --> 03:06:04.000
and, of course, such licensed and patent relations are primarily related to the corporate sector.

03:06:04.000 --> 03:06:10.000
Within the framework of the state, the form of international transfer of technology

03:06:10.000 --> 03:06:14.000
is an agreement on scientific and technical cooperation.

03:06:14.000 --> 03:06:19.000
Again, within the framework of the corporate and, above all, the state sector,

03:06:19.000 --> 03:06:25.000
there is an exchange of scientists, an agreement between the academy and the universities,

03:06:25.000 --> 03:06:29.000
that is, there is preparation of such personnel and specialists,

03:06:29.000 --> 03:06:36.000
such an international exchange, within which it is also possible to transfer technology.

03:06:36.000 --> 03:06:45.000
Another form is franchising, which assumes that within the framework of corporate structures,

03:06:45.000 --> 03:06:53.000
the company transfers the right to use its technologies or, let's say, the right to its trading brand.

03:06:53.000 --> 03:07:00.000
At the same time, this is not only a right, but a demand to support the business

03:07:00.000 --> 03:07:05.000
with such management and marketing techniques as developed in this company.

03:07:05.000 --> 03:07:10.000
Therefore, in this regard, it can also be considered that franchising is in a certain way,

03:07:10.000 --> 03:07:15.000
although it is not formally considered a direct transfer of technology,

03:07:15.000 --> 03:07:22.000
but in a certain measure, franchising also supports the international transfer of technology.

03:07:22.000 --> 03:07:27.000
Why are countries still trying to limit the transfer of technology?

03:07:27.000 --> 03:07:31.000
First of all, this is an aspiration to maintain technological leadership.

03:07:31.000 --> 03:07:36.000
Although any monopoly has two sides.

03:07:36.000 --> 03:07:40.000
On the one hand, yes, this country will be a technological leader for some time.

03:07:40.000 --> 03:07:44.000
On the other hand, this means that its technologies will get old over time,

03:07:44.000 --> 03:07:55.000
and it will need to invest a high level of investment in these industries or in scientific and research developments to maintain its technological leadership.

03:07:55.000 --> 03:07:58.000
That is, it will need to maintain its technological leadership.

03:07:58.000 --> 03:08:05.000
And it is not necessary that at some stage, during some technical investigations,

03:08:05.000 --> 03:08:11.000
this country, the technological leader, receives only one preference and dividends.

03:08:11.000 --> 03:08:17.000
The next reason for the limitation of the transfer of technology is the idea of national security.

03:08:17.000 --> 03:08:27.000
Of course, the state is trying to limit the distribution of military technologies.

03:08:27.000 --> 03:08:35.000
And, first of all, technologies related to the distribution of various means of mass destruction.

03:08:35.000 --> 03:08:42.000
On the other hand, within the framework of national security, there is a mass of double-purpose goods.

03:08:42.000 --> 03:08:49.000
And then these technological developments, of course, the state is interested in developing its economy

03:08:49.000 --> 03:08:55.000
and transferring from the military sector to the civil sector within its economy.

03:08:55.000 --> 03:09:00.000
The next reason is the conditions of international agreements.

03:09:00.000 --> 03:09:06.000
I have already mentioned the agreement between NATO member states, COCOM,

03:09:06.000 --> 03:09:13.000
in which the transfer of military technologies and double-purpose technologies is regulated.

03:09:13.000 --> 03:09:25.000
Of course, countries that have their own national legislation limiting the transfer of their technologies to the international sphere,

03:09:25.000 --> 03:09:28.000
they are very clearly tracking this point.

03:09:28.000 --> 03:09:37.000
In particular, the United States, when it tries to prove the illegality of a company in any country

03:09:37.000 --> 03:09:43.000
and the transfer of goods, the sale of goods, some product to a third country,

03:09:43.000 --> 03:09:48.000
proves that American technologies were involved in the development of its products.

03:09:48.000 --> 03:09:52.000
And often the percentage of this participation can reach 10-15%.

03:09:52.000 --> 03:10:00.000
This is a very small component, but due to this, the United States is basing the introduction of economic sanctions

03:10:00.000 --> 03:10:06.000
or some specific prohibitions for these companies or for the whole economy,

03:10:06.000 --> 03:10:18.000
which allowed the spread of technologies in those countries that, according to the United States, are politically unreliable.

03:10:18.000 --> 03:10:24.000
Accordingly, there are two mechanisms for regulating the international transfer of technologies.

03:10:25.000 --> 03:10:31.000
Of course, these are export control bodies, border customs control and indirect control

03:10:31.000 --> 03:10:44.000
through the issuance of patents, trade marks, licenses for know-how, and the completion of engineering services.

03:10:45.000 --> 03:11:01.000
Thus, in modern developed economies, they are trying to create an adequate mechanism for regulating the international transfer of technologies

03:11:01.000 --> 03:11:10.000
so that all those interests and contradictions related to the international distribution of technologies

03:11:10.000 --> 03:11:19.000
were finally allowed and did not restrain economic growth and spread of technological progress.

03:11:27.000 --> 03:11:33.000
The next topic we will discuss is the state regulation of foreign trade relations.

03:11:34.000 --> 03:11:42.000
First of all, let's pay attention to the objects of foreign trade regulation.

03:11:42.000 --> 03:11:48.000
In the narrow sense of the word, these are goods of export and import flows,

03:11:48.000 --> 03:11:57.000
and, of course, the structure of export and import, trade and payment balance issues.

03:11:57.000 --> 03:12:05.000
However, in the broad sense of the word, foreign trade relations also concern financial relations,

03:12:05.000 --> 03:12:13.000
since for the sale of goods by export and import, some payments must be made.

03:12:13.000 --> 03:12:18.000
Accordingly, financial relations are also an object of our consideration.

03:12:19.000 --> 03:12:26.000
Considering that foreign economic agents pay taxes to the state,

03:12:26.000 --> 03:12:34.000
the budget and economic growth are also related to the development of foreign trade relations

03:12:34.000 --> 03:12:37.000
and are an object of foreign trade regulation.

03:12:37.000 --> 03:12:47.000
It should be noted that domestic and foreign economic policy are closely interconnected.

03:12:47.000 --> 03:12:50.000
Take a look at the slide.

03:12:50.000 --> 03:13:00.000
Budget and tax policy can be a factor of foreign trade regulation.

03:13:00.000 --> 03:13:06.000
If we increase domestic taxes, domestic goods begin to cost more,

03:13:06.000 --> 03:13:15.000
and, therefore, they become less competitive compared to those goods offered by foreign agents.

03:13:15.000 --> 03:13:23.000
Accordingly, well-thought-out budget and tax policy can replace measures of open protectionism,

03:13:23.000 --> 03:13:30.000
when the state introduces quotas, tariffs, and other restrictions.

03:13:30.000 --> 03:13:36.000
On the other hand, protectionism is, in itself, the introduction of taxes.

03:13:36.000 --> 03:13:45.000
Such tariff policy implies fiscal goals, i.e. the replenishment of the budget.

03:13:45.000 --> 03:13:53.000
Based on this, some developing countries introduce policy of fairly tough protectionism,

03:13:53.000 --> 03:14:00.000
precisely because they do not have other sources of replenishment of the budget, or they are very limited.

03:14:00.000 --> 03:14:04.000
The next option is credit-money policy.

03:14:04.000 --> 03:14:08.000
It can also replace open protectionism,

03:14:08.000 --> 03:14:15.000
because credit-money policy regulates the money mass in the economy.

03:14:15.000 --> 03:14:21.000
As you know, a rapidly growing money mass can cause inflation,

03:14:21.000 --> 03:14:26.000
which, in turn, will lead to a decrease in the currency rate.

03:14:26.000 --> 03:14:32.000
It would seem that such a terrible internal situation as inflation

03:14:32.000 --> 03:14:36.000
and, in general, a decrease in purchasing power, for example, of the ruble,

03:14:36.000 --> 03:14:38.000
will negatively affect consumers.

03:14:38.000 --> 03:14:45.000
But, on the other hand, from the point of view of export, such a credit-money policy is even preferable.

03:14:45.000 --> 03:14:53.000
Why? Because the fall in the currency rate will stimulate relative cheapening of export products,

03:14:53.000 --> 03:14:59.000
and, accordingly, it will replace measures of open protectionism and support export.

03:14:59.000 --> 03:15:05.000
Subjects of foreign trade regulation, from the point of view of economists, are states,

03:15:05.000 --> 03:15:11.000
supranational institutions and various international structures.

03:15:11.000 --> 03:15:18.000
From the point of view of law, the only subject of foreign trade relations is only the state,

03:15:18.000 --> 03:15:29.000
because all the common international acts are, in the end, ratified by the national government.

03:15:29.000 --> 03:15:38.000
Based on this, the law-makers, I repeat, assume that the only subject of foreign trade relations is the state.

03:15:38.000 --> 03:15:43.000
An example of this is the process of Russia's entry into the WTO.

03:15:43.000 --> 03:15:58.000
Before we become a member of the WTO, Russia signs agreements with almost all 150 countries on a bilateral basis

03:15:58.000 --> 03:16:07.000
and ratifies these agreements at the national and state level.

03:16:08.000 --> 03:16:19.000
Foreign trade policy is a special sphere of economic relations, and the problems of the export of foreign trade policy are quite complex.

03:16:19.000 --> 03:16:28.000
The main problem is that such an economic policy should be exported, which would satisfy various groups, layers of the population.

03:16:28.000 --> 03:16:32.000
And here the question of economic efficiency and social justice arises.

03:16:32.000 --> 03:16:40.000
On the one hand, the market, market relations, competition contribute to the growth of economic efficiency,

03:16:40.000 --> 03:16:45.000
and then foreign trade policy should be quite liberal.

03:16:45.000 --> 03:16:55.000
And less efficient manufacturers, in particular national ones, can eventually leave the world market,

03:16:55.000 --> 03:17:03.000
because they irrationally organize production, irrationally use the factor of production.

03:17:03.000 --> 03:17:13.000
However, given the issue of social justice, such an effect on foreign trade policy would be negative for the country's development.

03:17:13.000 --> 03:17:19.000
Therefore, the second issue, the issue of social justice, is quite important.

03:17:19.000 --> 03:17:37.000
At least when we consider tariffs, we consider a number of aspects that push the government to include those positions in foreign trade policy

03:17:37.000 --> 03:17:43.000
that support the social protection of the citizens of the national economy.

03:17:43.000 --> 03:17:48.000
Thus, foreign trade policy is a compromise.

03:17:48.000 --> 03:17:59.000
A compromise that economic agents have chosen for this period of time, a compromise between economic efficiency and social justice.

03:17:59.000 --> 03:18:06.000
The level of this compromise depends on the level of society's development.

03:18:06.000 --> 03:18:10.000
What are the barriers to the efficiency of state regulation?

03:18:10.000 --> 03:18:18.000
Not everything goes smoothly, despite the fact that some legislative acts have been signed, some measures of foreign trade regulation have been developed.

03:18:18.000 --> 03:18:23.000
First of all, this is a rent-oriented behavior of politicians.

03:18:23.000 --> 03:18:30.000
Since foreign trade revenues are distributed unevenly, as was already said in the last lecture,

03:18:31.000 --> 03:18:41.000
the owners of specific factors, unique factors, usually receive more income when the world's prices rise from foreign trade,

03:18:41.000 --> 03:18:45.000
and the owners of neutral factors receive less income.

03:18:45.000 --> 03:18:52.000
Moreover, everyone who is engaged in import-replacing industries, when prices fall due to the development of international trade,

03:18:52.000 --> 03:18:55.000
becomes almost incompetent.

03:18:55.000 --> 03:18:58.000
These owners lose their income.

03:18:58.000 --> 03:19:07.000
So, the rent-oriented behavior of politicians is related to the group in which these politicians belong.

03:19:07.000 --> 03:19:16.000
The most relevant example is the policy related to agricultural parties.

03:19:16.000 --> 03:19:22.000
Of course, this is an import-replacing sector with its own problems,

03:19:22.000 --> 03:19:29.000
and, of course, representatives of agricultural parties will support a tough protectionist policy,

03:19:29.000 --> 03:19:32.000
which we have, for example, in the European Union.

03:19:32.000 --> 03:19:45.000
On the other hand, those politicians who belong to the group of such export-based raw materials industries as the oil industry, the gas industry,

03:19:45.000 --> 03:19:51.000
in the conditions of the modern market economy, when prices for these energy sources are constantly rising,

03:19:51.000 --> 03:19:59.000
will be interested in the development of liberalization of foreign trade relations and the expansion of foreign trade.

03:19:59.000 --> 03:20:10.000
And, in the end, both will lobby their decisions in state structures in order to carry out one or another type of economic policy.

03:20:11.000 --> 03:20:16.000
A subjective reason is also a barrier to the effectiveness of state regulation.

03:20:16.000 --> 03:20:26.000
A subjective reason is related to the development and literacy of those politicians who make state decisions.

03:20:26.000 --> 03:20:31.000
It is assumed that if they have a legal and economic education,

03:20:31.000 --> 03:20:37.000
they will be able to adequately deal with the problems of state regulation of the international economy.

03:20:37.000 --> 03:20:44.000
But, on the other hand, they may have their own subjective views on how economic policy should be carried out,

03:20:44.000 --> 03:20:48.000
and, accordingly, they may restrain the effectiveness of state regulation.

03:20:48.000 --> 03:20:53.000
The next aspect is the apparent distortion or change in policy.

03:20:53.000 --> 03:20:57.000
In fact, this is due to the two previous reasons.

03:20:58.000 --> 03:21:07.000
In principle, it is possible to develop very good laws and try to implement them in real practice.

03:21:07.000 --> 03:21:14.000
So, the officials who implement these economic laws in practice,

03:21:14.000 --> 03:21:25.000
they can distort the goals of politics, because they have their own group and personal interests,

03:21:25.000 --> 03:21:30.000
and they will lobby the interests of those groups to which they belong.

03:21:30.000 --> 03:21:34.000
The next reason is the influence of the surviving economic concepts.

03:21:34.000 --> 03:21:39.000
For example, state regulation in Russia.

03:21:39.000 --> 03:21:47.000
If we take the beginning of the 1990s, then the main postulate of foreign economic policy was liberalization.

03:21:48.000 --> 03:21:54.000
And within the framework of liberalization, they tried to increase export and import flows

03:21:54.000 --> 03:22:04.000
in order to enrich the Russian economy with scarce goods and to remove the problem of food and commodity shortages.

03:22:04.000 --> 03:22:16.000
But by 1995, the situation was such that such liberalism contradicted the interests of national producers.

03:22:16.000 --> 03:22:24.000
And, accordingly, liberalization became a surviving economic concept.

03:22:24.000 --> 03:22:32.000
Accordingly, during this period of time, a tougher foreign trade policy is being carried out in Russia.

03:22:32.000 --> 03:22:38.000
But Russia, starting from the same years, is negotiating the entry into the WTO.

03:22:38.000 --> 03:22:47.000
Accordingly, within the framework of such strategic goals, ideas and policies of liberalization must be carried out.

03:22:47.000 --> 03:22:56.000
Thus, now productionism is a surviving economic concept for the 2000s.

03:22:56.000 --> 03:23:12.000
As I said, the result of the production of compromise can be a kind of intermediate foreign trade policy, which takes into account various groups of interests.

03:23:12.000 --> 03:23:20.000
The degree of development of market relations is another reason for the decrease in the effectiveness of state regulation.

03:23:20.000 --> 03:23:32.000
As practice shows, countries with a developed legal system carry out state regulation measures more consistently.

03:23:32.000 --> 03:23:41.000
At the same time, countries with a transitional economy, the so-called transformation economy, or a catching economy,

03:23:42.000 --> 03:23:57.000
within the framework of a development of the legal base, the development of state policy is in more difficult circumstances.

03:23:57.000 --> 03:24:06.000
And, accordingly, the results of such state policy can be less effective.

03:24:06.000 --> 03:24:10.000
The next factor is the degree of openness of the economy.

03:24:10.000 --> 03:24:19.000
Oddly enough, all countries, at least 150 members of the WTO, are in favor of a consistent liberalization of foreign trade relations.

03:24:19.000 --> 03:24:26.000
But, as practice shows, as soon as countries become strongly involved in international economic relations,

03:24:26.000 --> 03:24:41.000
international labor division, as soon as their export-oriented sector develops, they become dependent on the problems of cataclysms that can occur in the world economy.

03:24:41.000 --> 03:24:55.000
Based on this, the effectiveness of state policy in these national economies will actually depend on the global economic situation.

03:24:56.000 --> 03:25:01.000
The authoritarian actions of the state. Another problem.

03:25:01.000 --> 03:25:05.000
And here the most typical example is the example of the state order.

03:25:05.000 --> 03:25:23.000
That is, by distributing state orders, our representatives of the state authorities will support various industrial groups, various industrial structures.

03:25:23.000 --> 03:25:35.000
And, accordingly, these actions of the government can have an authoritarian nature, because, again, they are carried out by certain officials,

03:25:35.000 --> 03:25:41.000
and there is also rent-oriented behavior and apparatus distortion.

03:25:41.000 --> 03:25:51.000
An example of such an authoritarian action of the state, for example, is the consequences of pollution of the environment.

03:25:51.000 --> 03:26:04.000
In particular, as you know, our corporation Minatom imports industrial waste from nuclear power plants to Russia.

03:26:04.000 --> 03:26:13.000
From the point of view of economic efficiency, this is, of course, a positive result, because investment is being made in the development of nuclear energy,

03:26:13.000 --> 03:26:20.000
and the state has a role in the development of such policies, as payment for the import of such waste.

03:26:20.000 --> 03:26:27.000
But on the other hand, from the point of view of social and global problems, they are only exacerbated.

03:26:27.000 --> 03:26:36.000
The next factor in reducing the effectiveness of state regulation is mutually exclusive directions of state policy.

03:26:36.000 --> 03:26:44.000
I have already said how the credit-money and budget-tax policy are connected with foreign trade policy.

03:26:44.000 --> 03:26:53.000
And, accordingly, the government can take measures of the Ministry of Finance, measures related to budget regulation, the Central Bank,

03:26:53.000 --> 03:27:02.000
and measures of credit-money policy that will completely level the steps that were taken in foreign trade policy.

03:27:03.000 --> 03:27:16.000
In this case, the simplest example is if the Central Bank for some reason refuses to support the reduction of the ruble exchange rate in modern conditions,

03:27:16.000 --> 03:27:30.000
the exchange rate begins to grow, and this, in turn, makes the prices of our export goods rise and makes them less competitive.

03:27:30.000 --> 03:27:42.000
And then, in the conditions of such a non-stop, the liberal foreign trade policy will, in fact, contradict the activity of the Central Bank,

03:27:42.000 --> 03:27:48.000
and the effectiveness of liberalization of foreign trade relations will be reduced.

03:27:50.000 --> 03:27:55.000
There are two main trends in the development of foreign trade policy.

03:27:55.000 --> 03:28:02.000
This is free-trading. The modern term for free-trading is liberalization of foreign trade relations.

03:28:02.000 --> 03:28:11.000
Free-trading implies the removal of all foreign trade restrictions and the development of free competition.

03:28:11.000 --> 03:28:20.000
Of course, the option of free-trading or liberal policy in its absolute full fulfillment is impossible.

03:28:20.000 --> 03:28:29.000
Each country has its own national interests, and there are also those industries and groups that need to be protected in terms of social issues.

03:28:29.000 --> 03:28:34.000
Therefore, there is no country with an ideal free-trading policy.

03:28:34.000 --> 03:28:41.000
You once studied the option of perfect competition in economic theory.

03:28:42.000 --> 03:28:51.000
Perfect competition, as well as absolute liberalization, are hypothetical models of development of foreign trade relations.

03:28:51.000 --> 03:28:57.000
Protectionism is another extreme in the development of foreign trade policy.

03:28:57.000 --> 03:29:02.000
It implies the protection of the domestic market from foreign competition.

03:29:02.000 --> 03:29:12.000
The second half of protectionist policy is related to the development and stimulation of export industries,

03:29:12.000 --> 03:29:28.000
and the state's activities to help export companies and to seize foreign trade markets.

03:29:30.000 --> 03:29:37.000
The history of foreign trade policy of the 20th century is quite dynamic.

03:29:37.000 --> 03:29:46.000
This history shows how, depending on the economic, domestic and foreign economic situation,

03:29:46.000 --> 03:29:56.000
governments of various countries fluctuate in the development of foreign trade policy from a policy of close liberalization

03:29:56.000 --> 03:30:01.000
to a policy that is associated with the introduction of stronger protectionist protective measures.

03:30:01.000 --> 03:30:07.000
If we take the beginning of the 20th century, the 1930s, this is a period of great depression,

03:30:07.000 --> 03:30:13.000
and, accordingly, the goal of foreign trade policy is to protect national producers.

03:30:13.000 --> 03:30:19.000
Therefore, foreign trade policy of this period can be called aggressive protectionism.

03:30:19.000 --> 03:30:30.000
It is characterized by trade wars, when one country or another introduces increasing foreign trade barriers,

03:30:30.000 --> 03:30:34.000
and the growth of tariff rates.

03:30:34.000 --> 03:30:42.000
After the Second World War, there is a long-term trend of liberalization of foreign trade relations.

03:30:42.000 --> 03:30:55.000
During the Second World War, many countries came to the conclusion that it was necessary to develop mutual interests,

03:30:55.000 --> 03:31:07.000
to develop export and import between countries, and, accordingly, the policy that would stimulate this development is liberalization policy.

03:31:07.000 --> 03:31:17.000
The most typical example of liberalization after the war is the Marshall Plan.

03:31:18.000 --> 03:31:32.000
Within this plan, which was developed in the United States, the United States provides economic and financial assistance to post-war European economies.

03:31:32.000 --> 03:31:40.000
But the conditions for such financial and investment support are liberalization of foreign trade relations.

03:31:40.000 --> 03:31:46.000
In the 1950s and 1960s, the process of liberalization continues.

03:31:46.000 --> 03:31:55.000
And it is during this period that the first agreements are made on the development of the international system,

03:31:55.000 --> 03:32:02.000
which has now developed into a system of the World Trade Organization.

03:32:02.000 --> 03:32:08.000
It is then that the first documents of the General Agreement on Trade Tariffs are signed.

03:32:08.000 --> 03:32:17.000
The 1970s are characterized by the exacerbation of the crisis situation in the world economy as a whole.

03:32:17.000 --> 03:32:31.000
As you know, in the 1970s there was a major structural, currency, financial, and raw material crisis in most developed economies.

03:32:32.000 --> 03:32:39.000
Accordingly, in these years, the goal of the governments of many countries is changing.

03:32:39.000 --> 03:32:44.000
They are starting to introduce strict measures of protectionism.

03:32:44.000 --> 03:32:48.000
A system of regional protectionism is being developed.

03:32:48.000 --> 03:32:55.000
This concerns the development of the relations of regional protectionism within the framework of Europe and the European Union.

03:32:56.000 --> 03:33:05.000
Starting in the 1990s, the development of the world economy is entering a certain stabilization process.

03:33:05.000 --> 03:33:13.000
And accordingly, in this period of time, since many countries do not experience financial and economic difficulties,

03:33:13.000 --> 03:33:18.000
issues of liberalization of foreign trade relations become relevant again.

03:33:19.000 --> 03:33:30.000
And it is at this time that the General Agreement on Trade Tariffs finally becomes an agreement within the framework of the World Trade Organization.

03:33:30.000 --> 03:33:37.000
The processes of such international mutual coordination of foreign trade policy are gaining strength.

03:33:37.000 --> 03:33:46.000
And these processes have maintained their trend since 2000 and in the 21st century.

03:33:48.000 --> 03:33:52.000
What are the characteristics of modern protectionism?

03:33:52.000 --> 03:33:55.000
First of all, it is local.

03:33:55.000 --> 03:34:03.000
And this local protectionism implies the allocation of various groups of countries to the world.

03:34:03.000 --> 03:34:07.000
Developed, developing, transitional economies.

03:34:07.000 --> 03:34:13.000
So, first of all, protectionism exists between developed countries.

03:34:13.000 --> 03:34:22.000
In which area? In the less protected area, associated with the processes of climate complications.

03:34:22.000 --> 03:34:24.000
This is agriculture.

03:34:24.000 --> 03:34:33.000
So far, the shifts to liquidation or reduction of agricultural protectionism are quite insignificant.

03:34:33.000 --> 03:34:44.000
And if we take the European Union, there are quite strict restrictions on the import of agricultural products from other non-allied countries.

03:34:44.000 --> 03:34:53.000
The next area of regional protectionism covers the textile industry, clothing production, steel.

03:34:54.000 --> 03:35:03.000
The second group of countries associated with international local protectionism is protectionism between developed and developing countries.

03:35:03.000 --> 03:35:18.000
The main problem here is that developing countries with export-oriented economies develop export, production, goods and services

03:35:18.000 --> 03:35:21.000
focused on consumption in developed countries.

03:35:21.000 --> 03:35:31.000
Accordingly, they exert quite a strong pressure on competition in their exports, which is formed on the territory of developed countries.

03:35:31.000 --> 03:35:40.000
And in this regard, developed countries, protecting their national producers, introduce various trade restrictions,

03:35:40.000 --> 03:35:49.000
not only tax, but also various quantitative restrictions, quotas on the import of goods from developing countries.

03:35:49.000 --> 03:35:58.000
And the last group of countries associated with local protectionism is developing countries.

03:35:58.000 --> 03:36:04.000
There is a problematic relationship between them on goods of traditional export.

03:36:05.000 --> 03:36:11.000
What are the characteristics of modern liberalization and modern protectionism?

03:36:11.000 --> 03:36:25.000
First, within the framework of modern processes of liberalization, the sphere of tools, regulating mechanisms of foreign trade relations is expanding.

03:36:25.000 --> 03:36:46.000
In addition to tariffs, various forms of financial support are applied, which are less predictable and less subject to international agreements.

03:36:46.000 --> 03:36:52.000
The next feature of modern liberalization is multilateral liberalization of foreign trade exchanges.

03:36:52.000 --> 03:36:59.000
First of all, this is a relationship between countries within the framework of the negotiation process of the World Trade Organization.

03:36:59.000 --> 03:37:05.000
In general, modern liberalization is associated with a decrease in the overall level of all barriers.

03:37:05.000 --> 03:37:11.000
And this, as I said, is a long-term trend of the 21st century.

03:37:12.000 --> 03:37:25.000
Regional integration associated with the formation of integration unions is a form of modern world space that is developing rapidly.

03:37:25.000 --> 03:37:34.000
Regional integration has features of both liberalization and protectionism.

03:37:34.000 --> 03:37:43.000
Countries that join integration unions remove trade barriers between them.

03:37:43.000 --> 03:37:52.000
But in relation to third countries, they develop a common system of tariff barriers and other methods of protectionist protection.

03:37:52.000 --> 03:37:59.000
In this case, economic theory suggests taking into account two effects of the development of regional integration.

03:38:00.000 --> 03:38:05.000
The effect of creating trade and the effect of rejecting trade.

03:38:05.000 --> 03:38:23.000
The effect of creating trade is due to the fact that if countries that have joined the integration union for the development of international economic relations

03:38:23.000 --> 03:38:35.000
switch and develop production in their own countries, focused on international flow,

03:38:35.000 --> 03:38:40.000
because this production is cheaper, more efficient, and more rational.

03:38:40.000 --> 03:38:47.000
Then, the countries that are members of the integration union develop international trade,

03:38:47.000 --> 03:38:51.000
increase the volume of international trade within their integration group.

03:38:51.000 --> 03:39:00.000
The second effect of rejecting trade is due to the fact that low costs and more efficient production organization

03:39:00.000 --> 03:39:07.000
can be in those countries that, as a result of the formation of the integration union, became outsiders.

03:39:07.000 --> 03:39:11.000
And then, tariff restrictions apply against them.

03:39:11.000 --> 03:39:18.000
They limit their flow of effectively created products to the integration market.

03:39:18.000 --> 03:39:28.000
And the countries that are members of the integration union start consuming goods with higher costs, goods of less efficient production.

03:39:28.000 --> 03:39:36.000
This is a variant of economic relations, which is connected with the effect of rejecting trade.

03:39:36.000 --> 03:39:39.000
External trade flows are reduced.

03:39:40.000 --> 03:39:48.000
If we consider the forms of protectionism, modern theory suggests the following forms.

03:39:48.000 --> 03:39:50.000
First of all, selective protectionism.

03:39:50.000 --> 03:40:01.000
It is assumed that selective protectionism is a measure aimed at a certain economic activity.

03:40:02.000 --> 03:40:12.000
It may not even be used for goods created in a certain industry, such as textiles, but only for certain groups of goods.

03:40:12.000 --> 03:40:20.000
Such selective protectionism is usually associated with the introduction of seasonal duties, which we will discuss later.

03:40:20.000 --> 03:40:22.000
Industrial protectionism.

03:40:22.000 --> 03:40:34.000
A typical example of industrial protectionism is the protectionism of the EU countries in the defense of their national agricultural production.

03:40:34.000 --> 03:40:36.000
Hidden protectionism.

03:40:36.000 --> 03:40:46.000
Hidden protectionism implies measures of external trade regulation that are difficult to take into account.

03:40:46.000 --> 03:40:48.000
First of all, these are financial measures.

03:40:48.000 --> 03:40:50.000
Open protectionism.

03:40:50.000 --> 03:40:59.000
Such a form of protectionism implies the introduction of various duties or quantitative restrictions.

03:40:59.000 --> 03:41:10.000
Open protectionism is more subject to state regulation and international economic agreements.

03:41:10.000 --> 03:41:17.000
Open protectionism measures are currently being reduced.

03:41:17.000 --> 03:41:21.000
Most countries are trying to use hidden protectionism.

03:41:21.000 --> 03:41:26.000
What are the arguments for and against protectionism?

03:41:27.000 --> 03:41:34.000
In general, economic theory has a lot of works devoted to this argument.

03:41:34.000 --> 03:41:40.000
There are authors who bring up to 140 positions to the list of arguments for and against.

03:41:40.000 --> 03:41:42.000
But we will consider only some of them.

03:41:42.000 --> 03:41:48.000
The argument against protectionism is first of all promoted by the classical neoclassical school.

03:41:48.000 --> 03:41:53.000
In this case, there is such a concept of the second best.

03:41:53.000 --> 03:41:55.000
What does it mean?

03:41:55.000 --> 03:42:05.000
The idea is that there can be nothing better than liberal relations, development of international trade for countries, economic growth.

03:42:05.000 --> 03:42:09.000
There is no second best compared to open economy.

03:42:09.000 --> 03:42:18.000
The classics are Adam Smith, Ricardo, and the modern representatives of this direction, the monetarists.

03:42:19.000 --> 03:42:32.000
The next position for inclusion of protectionism as a measure of state regulation is the doctrine of unused production factors.

03:42:32.000 --> 03:42:34.000
What does it mean?

03:42:34.000 --> 03:42:45.000
When a country in which you want to export your product is somehow protected from your trade flows with protectionism measures,

03:42:45.000 --> 03:42:48.000
you still have an opportunity to enter this market.

03:42:48.000 --> 03:42:53.000
Then you make investments and organize production in the territory of these countries.

03:42:53.000 --> 03:43:01.000
Moreover, you can use labor or import labor to your territory.

03:43:01.000 --> 03:43:08.000
Thus, the doctrine of unused production factors shows that in such a difficult situation of foreign trade restrictions,

03:43:08.000 --> 03:43:10.000
countries still have a way out.

03:43:10.000 --> 03:43:16.000
Moreover, this way out contributes to the general development of national economies and the global economy as a whole.

03:43:16.000 --> 03:43:22.000
The next significant argument for the introduction of protectionism is the protection of jobs.

03:43:22.000 --> 03:43:26.000
This is a social argument.

03:43:26.000 --> 03:43:34.000
Let's imagine cities where there is a single enterprise and local national personnel can be employed.

03:43:34.000 --> 03:43:40.000
Certainly, from the point of view of the development of these cities and territories,

03:43:40.000 --> 03:43:45.000
the state will have to support the existence of these industries for some time,

03:43:45.000 --> 03:43:51.000
even if they are less competitive in the global economic space.

03:43:51.000 --> 03:43:56.000
The concept of economic security is another argument for protectionism.

03:43:56.000 --> 03:44:03.000
It is due to the fact that any country assumes the worst course of events.

03:44:03.000 --> 03:44:13.000
In the event of international political conflicts, each country should have a reserve for the development of its industries

03:44:13.000 --> 03:44:19.000
and the ability to produce products in a closed national space.

03:44:19.000 --> 03:44:25.000
Nevertheless, this concept has certainly been modernized in modern conditions.

03:44:25.000 --> 03:44:31.000
It is assumed that the introduction of a system that is completely closed,

03:44:31.000 --> 03:44:35.000
limited by international economic ties and the economy, will not be implemented.

03:44:35.000 --> 03:44:39.000
The next argument is for the protection of the emerging national industries.

03:44:39.000 --> 03:44:43.000
This argument is usually made by developing countries,

03:44:44.000 --> 03:44:57.000
because for them export-oriented production is the main form of national income.

03:44:57.000 --> 03:45:04.000
And since in these countries the industry is developing,

03:45:04.000 --> 03:45:07.000
they become industrial abroad,

03:45:07.000 --> 03:45:22.000
then a short-term protection of these emerging industrial industries is very important for these countries.

03:45:22.000 --> 03:45:29.000
And is perceived by the world community as a normal form of protection from international competition.

03:45:30.000 --> 03:45:35.000
Now let's look at the tools of state regulation of foreign trade.

03:45:35.000 --> 03:45:41.000
There are quite a lot of them, and they can be classified according to different principles.

03:45:41.000 --> 03:45:49.000
In general, the entire group of measures for the protection of the national economy, protectionist measures,

03:45:49.000 --> 03:45:54.000
is divided into two large groups, tariff and non-tariff barriers.

03:45:55.000 --> 03:46:04.000
If we take the tariff barriers, then there are two most unique forms,

03:46:04.000 --> 03:46:09.000
these are customs duties and tariff quotas, which we will talk about later.

03:46:09.000 --> 03:46:14.000
Non-tariff measures are quantitative restrictions.

03:46:14.000 --> 03:46:18.000
This type of restriction is not welcomed by the international community,

03:46:18.000 --> 03:46:22.000
because they completely block trade flows.

03:46:22.000 --> 03:46:30.000
As I said, the hidden measures of protectionism are quite developed in modern conditions,

03:46:30.000 --> 03:46:33.000
and developed countries are trying to resort to them,

03:46:33.000 --> 03:46:38.000
because it is difficult to take them into account, and, accordingly, it is difficult for other countries,

03:46:38.000 --> 03:46:43.000
counteragents to make claims to the national economy and their governments on the introduction of hidden measures.

03:46:43.000 --> 03:46:49.000
A special block of state regulation tools is the financial measures of protectionism.

03:46:50.000 --> 03:46:56.000
This includes subsidies, loans and various types of sanctions, including dumping.

03:46:56.000 --> 03:47:04.000
Macroeconomic measures can be classified into a separate group,

03:47:04.000 --> 03:47:08.000
and can be attributed to the hidden measures of protectionism.

03:47:08.000 --> 03:47:15.000
As I said, macroeconomic policy is strongly interconnected with foreign policy,

03:47:16.000 --> 03:47:21.000
and therefore, by means of credit-money or budget-tax policy,

03:47:21.000 --> 03:47:28.000
you can replace some of the methods that are used in the framework of the state's tariff policy.

03:47:28.000 --> 03:47:32.000
The last group is quantitative financial measures.

03:47:32.000 --> 03:47:38.000
This is a special group, because it is associated with economic sanctions.

03:47:38.000 --> 03:47:47.000
In principle, economic sanctions are not considered a common measure of state foreign policy,

03:47:47.000 --> 03:47:53.000
because they are introduced primarily to solve some political problems.

03:47:53.000 --> 03:48:02.000
But since economic sanctions use methods that block export and import flows,

03:48:02.000 --> 03:48:11.000
they are also subject to economic science and the consequences of economic sanctions.

03:48:11.000 --> 03:48:21.000
The methods of imposing sanctions are understood in economic theory and in the theory of international economic relations.

03:48:22.000 --> 03:48:29.000
Let's move on to the first group of protectionist measures,

03:48:29.000 --> 03:48:33.000
tariff measures and customs duties.

03:48:33.000 --> 03:48:39.000
The difference between the terms of duties and tariffs.

03:48:39.000 --> 03:48:49.000
As you know, a duty is a certain tax that is charged when importing or exporting goods.

03:48:50.000 --> 03:49:00.000
But since these duties are differentiated and varied in relation to different groups of goods or countries,

03:49:00.000 --> 03:49:04.000
they are collected in a table called a tariff.

03:49:04.000 --> 03:49:09.000
A similar tariff can be attributed to, for example, wages,

03:49:09.000 --> 03:49:16.000
that is, a grid of various levels of labor payment for various types of activities.

03:49:16.000 --> 03:49:23.000
All customs duties are collected in a certain grid, which is called a tariff.

03:49:23.000 --> 03:49:27.000
That is why customs duties are considered a tariff measure.

03:49:27.000 --> 03:49:29.000
What are the functions of customs duties?

03:49:29.000 --> 03:49:31.000
First of all, the fiscal function.

03:49:31.000 --> 03:49:34.000
Why? Because it is a means of redistributing income.

03:49:34.000 --> 03:49:40.000
If the fiscal goals are prevailing,

03:49:41.000 --> 03:49:47.000
then such a tariff policy is not ideal.

03:49:47.000 --> 03:49:58.000
Since the state understands that the general development of the economy and international economic relations

03:49:58.000 --> 03:50:04.000
is a necessary component of modern economic development.

03:50:05.000 --> 03:50:13.000
Therefore, the fiscal goal is present, but for developed countries it is a secondary goal.

03:50:13.000 --> 03:50:20.000
But for transitional economies, which have recently experienced some financial problems,

03:50:20.000 --> 03:50:26.000
which have a shortage of trade and payment balance, which have a budget deficit,

03:50:26.000 --> 03:50:34.000
these countries certainly use customs duties as a means of receiving tax payments

03:50:34.000 --> 03:50:37.000
and as a means of replenishing the budget.

03:50:37.000 --> 03:50:41.000
The next function is protectionist.

03:50:41.000 --> 03:50:50.000
In this case, it is assumed that customs duties help us protect certain industries from international competition

03:50:50.000 --> 03:50:55.000
and, accordingly, help the development of certain industries.

03:50:55.000 --> 03:51:02.000
In the end, such protectionism helps to influence the payment balance.

03:51:02.000 --> 03:51:10.000
If the payment balance is negative and the import flows are too large and pressure the internal competition,

03:51:10.000 --> 03:51:14.000
the state of the domestic national economy,

03:51:14.000 --> 03:51:25.000
the implementation of protectionism measures to reduce import in a certain period of time is acceptable.

03:51:25.000 --> 03:51:28.000
The next function is balance.

03:51:28.000 --> 03:51:37.000
It is assumed that export and import are developed primarily out of a lack of supply and demand in the domestic market.

03:51:37.000 --> 03:51:41.000
If we have a shortage of goods in the domestic market,

03:51:41.000 --> 03:51:49.000
we must liberalize our foreign trade relations and expand the import flow.

03:51:49.000 --> 03:51:52.000
If, on the contrary, there is a situation of excess of goods,

03:51:52.000 --> 03:51:59.000
we must help export of excess goods abroad in every possible way.

03:51:59.000 --> 03:52:03.000
A number of basic principles of tariff policy are highlighted.

03:52:03.000 --> 03:52:06.000
First of all, this is the principle of tariff escalation.

03:52:06.000 --> 03:52:08.000
What does it mean?

03:52:08.000 --> 03:52:15.000
All countries, having limited resources, primarily raw materials,

03:52:15.000 --> 03:52:20.000
are interested in importing raw materials to their territories,

03:52:20.000 --> 03:52:22.000
because they are unrecoverable.

03:52:22.000 --> 03:52:33.000
Based on this, the principle of tariff escalation assumes that tariff duties are low enough for some raw materials,

03:52:33.000 --> 03:52:39.000
or are generally canceled depending on the economic situation in the domestic economy.

03:52:39.000 --> 03:52:48.000
If we import ready-made products, the higher the degree of processing of this ready-made product, the higher the tariff barriers.

03:52:48.000 --> 03:52:58.000
In particular, for the components that are later used in national production for the assembly of ready-made products in the domestic economy,

03:52:58.000 --> 03:53:02.000
the tariff barriers are usually lower than for ready-made products.

03:53:02.000 --> 03:53:07.000
The simplest example is the tariff for components for computers,

03:53:07.000 --> 03:53:16.000
which is lower than the tariff for the import of ready-made computers from other countries.

03:53:16.000 --> 03:53:19.000
What is the optimal tariff?

03:53:19.000 --> 03:53:22.000
This principle is more theoretical than practical.

03:53:23.000 --> 03:53:35.000
It was developed in the EU Institutes, when the question was discussed about what tariffs should be used,

03:53:35.000 --> 03:53:39.000
what should be the protectionist measures system within the EU.

03:53:39.000 --> 03:53:46.000
The optimal tariff is the tariff that does not maximize the tax collection.

03:53:46.000 --> 03:53:52.000
The optimal tariff is not the one that allows the fiscal function of the tariff,

03:53:52.000 --> 03:53:57.000
but the one that does not worsen the position of national consumers,

03:53:57.000 --> 03:54:05.000
does not worsen the overall indicators of the country's economic growth.

03:54:05.000 --> 03:54:10.000
To some extent, the idea of ​​an optimal tariff is a general theoretical idea,

03:54:10.000 --> 03:54:18.000
but nevertheless, when developing the protectionist measures system in Western Europe, this idea was used.

03:54:18.000 --> 03:54:23.000
What is the classification of customs duties?

03:54:23.000 --> 03:54:30.000
We can divide them into at least three groups, first of all, in terms of collection methods.

03:54:30.000 --> 03:54:32.000
Advalorous duties.

03:54:33.000 --> 03:54:41.000
The name itself, Advalorous, means that this is a tax that is imposed based on the cost of the product,

03:54:41.000 --> 03:54:43.000
that is, a certain tax on the price of the product.

03:54:43.000 --> 03:54:45.000
Specific.

03:54:45.000 --> 03:54:55.000
In this case, it is assumed that the tax is imposed based on the physiological characteristics of the product,

03:54:56.000 --> 03:55:04.000
that is, on tons, square meters, liters of engine volume, and so on.

03:55:04.000 --> 03:55:06.000
Combined duties.

03:55:06.000 --> 03:55:11.000
In this case, these are the duties that use both the first and the second principle.

03:55:11.000 --> 03:55:20.000
When, for example, a percentage tax is declared on the importation of a product,

03:55:20.000 --> 03:55:29.000
it is also indicated that the total cost of the tax should not exceed, for example, 5 euros per ton.

03:55:29.000 --> 03:55:37.000
In terms of the object of application, customs duties are divided into import, export and transit.

03:55:37.000 --> 03:55:43.000
As you can see, in this case, the account of flows is assumed.

03:55:43.000 --> 03:55:52.000
Of course, in the world community, customs duties are kept for the import flow.

03:55:52.000 --> 03:56:02.000
And we have already considered arguments for such a method of import duties.

03:56:02.000 --> 03:56:10.000
As for the export flow, developed countries are not trying to increase the price of their export goods.

03:56:10.000 --> 03:56:15.000
Based on this, export taxes are usually not applied in developed countries.

03:56:15.000 --> 03:56:21.000
For example, according to US legislation, there are no tariff restrictions on US exports.

03:56:21.000 --> 03:56:25.000
On the other hand, if we take, for example, Russia,

03:56:25.000 --> 03:56:34.000
we know that we have export duties for the export of oil and gas, that is, energy sources.

03:56:34.000 --> 03:56:57.000
The purpose of such export duties is to redistribute the budget for the benefit of the state.

03:56:57.000 --> 03:57:03.000
Therefore, the purpose of such export duties is redistribution of the fiscal function.

03:57:03.000 --> 03:57:13.000
Further, our domestic consumers are also interested, especially in the summer, in the agricultural trend of energy consumption.

03:57:13.000 --> 03:57:20.000
Accordingly, in order to somehow contain the flow of these goods for export at this time,

03:57:20.000 --> 03:57:26.000
given that the internal prices for energy are usually contained by the lower, less profitable exporter,

03:57:26.000 --> 03:57:34.000
the introduction of export duties allows to regulate these flows and protect the national consumer

03:57:34.000 --> 03:57:42.000
and the deficit, or very important, product, to reorient to the domestic market.

03:57:42.000 --> 03:57:51.000
Transit duties are usually taken for moving through the economic territory of a country some goods from one country to another.

03:57:51.000 --> 03:57:55.000
Usually, transit duties are excluded from developed countries.

03:57:55.000 --> 03:58:02.000
Nevertheless, for developing countries, I repeat, for them and especially for moving economies,

03:58:02.000 --> 03:58:05.000
transit duties are a means of replenishing the budget.

03:58:05.000 --> 03:58:14.000
Here is an example of Belarus' transit duties on the export of Russian gas to Ukraine, and so on.

03:58:14.000 --> 03:58:18.000
Usually, of course, there are big disputes about transit duties.

03:58:18.000 --> 03:58:23.000
In this case, these national economies replenish their budget due to transit duties.

03:58:23.000 --> 03:58:29.000
In terms of impact, duties are divided into seasonal, compensation, and anti-dumping.

03:58:29.000 --> 03:58:38.000
Seasonal duties are usually introduced into the goods flow depending on the demand and supply in some seasonal period.

03:58:38.000 --> 03:58:43.000
For example, in the summer, seasonal duties can be introduced into the import of agricultural products

03:58:44.000 --> 03:58:48.000
in order to protect the national agricultural producers.

03:58:48.000 --> 03:58:59.000
Compensation duties, as well as anti-dumping duties, are measures of protection.

03:59:00.000 --> 03:59:18.000
If, for example, the government or some other economic agents find out that in this case the export to the country is supported by financial support of some other measures,

03:59:18.000 --> 03:59:27.000
then this state, against the support of other government of export, can introduce anti-dumping duties.

03:59:27.000 --> 03:59:35.000
Of course, then a trade war begins, and it is better to move on to the coordination of their positions

03:59:35.000 --> 03:59:42.000
and, in general, to mutually reduce these flows, and then compensation duties cannot be introduced.

03:59:42.000 --> 03:59:53.000
Anti-dumping duties are aimed at punishing those companies that try to import at low prices in order to seize the domestic market.

03:59:53.000 --> 04:00:02.000
What are the strong and weak sides of the method of taking tariffs?

04:00:02.000 --> 04:00:06.000
Anti-dumping duties have one positive effect.

04:00:06.000 --> 04:00:10.000
They maintain the same level of protection of the domestic market when prices change.

04:00:10.000 --> 04:00:14.000
The negative side is the problem of customs valuation of the product's cost.

04:00:15.000 --> 04:00:24.000
Of course, the importer, when offering a product that is of a certain cost to our domestic market,

04:00:24.000 --> 04:00:32.000
tries to reduce this cost in various ways and develops a whole system of measures in modern law,

04:00:32.000 --> 04:00:37.000
such as re-checking and re-evaluating the cost of the product.

04:00:37.000 --> 04:00:42.000
Specific duties are quite simple to administer.

04:00:42.000 --> 04:00:51.000
It is clear that if you take a tax for a cubic meter or a square meter, for some weight, then it is enough to simply introduce them.

04:00:51.000 --> 04:01:00.000
But the level of protection of these specific duties greatly depends on the fluctuation of world prices.

04:01:00.000 --> 04:01:08.000
In this case, if you import a product that has become much cheaper on the world market,

04:01:08.000 --> 04:01:16.000
and you take a tax only from a ton or another physical unit, then you certainly do not contain this flow,

04:01:16.000 --> 04:01:25.000
because the demand for such a product on the domestic market will begin to increase, and these products will be competitive for national manufacturers.

04:01:25.000 --> 04:01:29.000
As for the tariff quota, what is this measure?

04:01:29.000 --> 04:01:44.000
The tariff quota assumes that the tax is increased after the agreed volume of import is already brought to the national territory.

04:01:44.000 --> 04:01:46.000
What does this mean?

04:01:46.000 --> 04:01:55.000
For example, we decided to introduce 20 tons, and the tariff quota says that if you import 10 tons, then the tax is 2%.

04:01:55.000 --> 04:02:00.000
But if you import something above 10 tons, then the tax becomes 15%.

04:02:00.000 --> 04:02:02.000
This is the tariff quota method.

04:02:02.000 --> 04:02:06.000
What are the advantages of the tariff quota?

04:02:06.000 --> 04:02:10.000
In this case, it is not a complete physical restriction of export or import.

04:02:11.000 --> 04:02:19.000
It is assumed that companies that want to seize our national market or somehow reinforce it,

04:02:19.000 --> 04:02:29.000
will agree to pay a higher tax and, in the end, will introduce the product that they decided to offer to our national consumer.

04:02:29.000 --> 04:02:33.000
That is, the external trade flow is not completely closed.

04:02:33.000 --> 04:02:36.000
This is, of course, a strong side of the tariff quota.

04:02:37.000 --> 04:02:40.000
External trade quantitative measures.

04:02:40.000 --> 04:02:48.000
This is a fairly large block of measures, and it includes the most common quantitative restrictions,

04:02:48.000 --> 04:03:02.000
such as quotas, licensing, import contingency, anti-dumping duties, compensation duties, and voluntary export restrictions, as well as compensation fees.

04:03:02.000 --> 04:03:13.000
Quotas are the measure against which agreements are first and foremost within the framework of the World Trade Organization.

04:03:13.000 --> 04:03:22.000
Why? Because quotas are a physical restriction of the flow of export and import, and more than some volume can practically be imported or exported.

04:03:22.000 --> 04:03:34.000
Quotas are used by developed countries of the world, and this mainly applies to agricultural products, textile imports, or metals in these countries.

04:03:34.000 --> 04:03:41.000
In particular, Russia imports metals within the framework of the quota.

04:03:41.000 --> 04:03:54.000
Of course, these quotas are based on intergovernmental agreements, and, nevertheless, there are such physical restrictions of the flow of export and import.

04:03:54.000 --> 04:04:07.000
Licensing is also a form of physical restriction of external trade flows, since it implies a limited issuance of licenses.

04:04:07.000 --> 04:04:18.000
Some firms give, some do not. It is assumed that licenses can be issued for a limited volume of export and import operations.

04:04:18.000 --> 04:04:27.000
Nevertheless, licenses can be general, and then there is no physical restriction of licensed goods.

04:04:27.000 --> 04:04:42.000
Licenses are usually issued for the export of gold, diamonds, and other rare valuable goods, to either limit its export, or, on the contrary, limit its import,

04:04:42.000 --> 04:04:51.000
since the situation of demand and supply in the domestic market of the countries' economies is changing.

04:04:52.000 --> 04:04:58.000
Import contingency. Such a complex name is associated with seasonal quotas.

04:04:58.000 --> 04:05:08.000
That is, a certain contingent of goods, a certain list of goods is subject to a physical restriction of import or export.

04:05:08.000 --> 04:05:12.000
I have already mentioned anti-dumping and compensation duties.

04:05:12.000 --> 04:05:24.000
They are associated with the fact that when countries are not interested in importing some goods at too cheap prices,

04:05:24.000 --> 04:05:34.000
or cheap prices are associated with the fact that this export is supported by various financial methods by the governments of other states,

04:05:34.000 --> 04:05:47.000
then these anti-dumping and compensation duties are considered fair and are introduced on the basis of judicial proceedings.

04:05:47.000 --> 04:05:55.000
Because, in principle, it is impossible to introduce an anti-dumping and compensation duty without a fairly complete consideration of the problem.

04:05:55.000 --> 04:06:06.000
That is, it is necessary to take into account the position of the parties, why this price was so low, or why a particular tax was introduced.

04:06:06.000 --> 04:06:10.000
Voluntary export restrictions. Voluntary in quotation marks. Why?

04:06:10.000 --> 04:06:20.000
Because it is assumed that the country introducing voluntary export restrictions, as a result of negotiations with its counterpart, with another country,

04:06:20.000 --> 04:06:30.000
understands that if it does not voluntarily limit its export, then various restrictive measures will be introduced against it,

04:06:30.000 --> 04:06:35.000
in the form of quotas, licenses, or even compensation duties.

04:06:35.000 --> 04:06:45.000
Voluntary export restrictions are usually introduced when the country of the importer has a negative trade balance with this country,

04:06:45.000 --> 04:06:48.000
that is, there is a fairly strong import flow.

04:06:48.000 --> 04:06:56.000
Such voluntary export restrictions exist in Russia, with many Western European countries, for the export of metals,

04:06:56.000 --> 04:07:02.000
in Japan, the United States, for the export of Japanese food to the United States.

04:07:03.000 --> 04:07:09.000
In the same row of quantitative restrictions are the compensation duties,

04:07:09.000 --> 04:07:23.000
since they are higher than any other measures that stimulate export, which were introduced by importers earlier,

04:07:23.000 --> 04:07:28.000
and that is why their price, their goods are cheaper.

04:07:29.000 --> 04:07:35.000
There are various ways to distribute licenses. First of all, it is an auction-based competition.

04:07:35.000 --> 04:07:41.000
The second option is a system of explicit preferences, and the third option is competition on an initial basis.

04:07:41.000 --> 04:07:53.000
An auction-based competition is the most preferable option, because in this case those who are trying to get a license for export or import,

04:07:53.000 --> 04:08:10.000
they compete in terms of the purchase of licenses, and, accordingly, the state wins from the sale of such a license agreement.

04:08:10.000 --> 04:08:17.000
If we have an explicit preferences system, it is usually used by the government in the case

04:08:17.000 --> 04:08:25.000
if these are already permanent counteragents and the companies have recommended themselves on the good side,

04:08:25.000 --> 04:08:35.000
and, accordingly, there is no competition here, and the invitation or distribution of licenses is carried out directly by officials.

04:08:35.000 --> 04:08:41.000
Competition on a non-price basis is also a significant form of distribution of licenses,

04:08:41.000 --> 04:08:53.000
since it is assumed that the main parameter of victory in this competition is some non-price characteristics of the product.

04:08:53.000 --> 04:08:59.000
Now let's look at the types of export support. First of all, this is direct export stimulation.

04:09:00.000 --> 04:09:07.000
It is assumed that the state distributes part of the budget, for example, to agricultural producers,

04:09:07.000 --> 04:09:22.000
and, moreover, in the EU, some taxes on imports after their collection by targeted programs are redistributed to agricultural products.

04:09:22.000 --> 04:09:28.000
Export subsidies for agricultural products are difficult to track,

04:09:28.000 --> 04:09:40.000
since the motivation of these subsidies is related to the fact that the domestic national economy is supported,

04:09:40.000 --> 04:09:47.000
and, accordingly, the domestic industry, for example, agriculture or some industry of machinery.

04:09:47.000 --> 04:09:57.000
Direct export stimulation is primarily associated with various financial types of support,

04:09:57.000 --> 04:10:06.000
such as the benefit lending of exports. Benefits are provided both in terms of terms and interest rates, and by sources of funds.

04:10:06.000 --> 04:10:14.000
Financial assistance to developing countries is a form that is used by quite actively developed countries.

04:10:14.000 --> 04:10:27.000
It is assumed that the financial assistance provided to these countries will be spent on the purchase of goods that will be exported from these developed countries.

04:10:27.000 --> 04:10:40.000
Again, the motivation of such financial assistance is associated with social issues, and it is quite difficult to prove the benefits of exporters.

04:10:41.000 --> 04:10:48.000
The next form is state insurance. It is also developed to a lesser extent in developed countries,

04:10:48.000 --> 04:11:03.000
when the state, in a legislative order, insures and guarantees export firms from various risks in the territories of various countries.

04:11:03.000 --> 04:11:18.000
These can be insurance of loans, various political risks, and not only risks related to weather conditions, which will most likely be insured by private firms.

04:11:18.000 --> 04:11:30.000
Tax benefits on domestic taxes. In this case, this is a fairly hidden form of export support,

04:11:30.000 --> 04:11:39.000
since domestic tax benefits can be distributed to a large number of types of goods.

04:11:39.000 --> 04:11:53.000
Again, it is quite difficult to prove that these tax benefits were aimed at the support of exporters, and not at the development of national economic industries.

04:11:54.000 --> 04:12:08.000
State information assistance. In this case, it is assumed that the state can subsidize or finance the organization of exhibitions, international salons.

04:12:08.000 --> 04:12:31.000
Of course, firms that provide their goods and protect the country's honor at these exhibitions receive additional information about possible competitors and innovations introduced by foreign firms.

04:12:32.000 --> 04:12:43.000
The international export control system was mainly developed during the Cold War.

04:12:43.000 --> 04:12:52.000
The example I am giving you is the existence of the Co-Competition Committee for the Control of Export.

04:12:52.000 --> 04:13:05.000
This committee existed within the framework of NATO countries, and within this committee programs were developed for the control of arms,

04:13:05.000 --> 04:13:17.000
for the control of the production of nuclear energy, and also for the control of the production of industrial goods.

04:13:17.000 --> 04:13:36.000
It should be said that in modern conditions, each country has developed laws and legislative acts that allow such international control, both within and outside the framework of the Co-Competition Committee.

04:13:36.000 --> 04:13:54.000
In particular, it is possible that in the conditions of integration and cooperation between countries, although measures may be aimed at one particular country for political purposes, third, independent countries may suffer.

04:13:54.000 --> 04:14:13.000
In this case, the example I would like to consider is the production of a military aircraft in Russia. Suppliers of components and systems for this aircraft are a number of Western European countries.

04:14:13.000 --> 04:14:31.000
Nevertheless, within the framework of monitoring the transfer of military technologies to the United States, a number of Western European companies were prohibited from exporting components for the production of such an aircraft.

04:14:31.000 --> 04:14:47.000
Sanctions imposed by the US government on Sukhoi in connection with the issue of arms supply to Iran were lifted in the fall of 2006.

04:14:47.000 --> 04:15:05.000
Nevertheless, the countries and suppliers of components for the production of this aircraft, the DeskJet, were under pressure and influence.

04:15:05.000 --> 04:15:25.000
What are the modern features of export control? First of all, in modern conditions, there is a transition from export control to export control of strategically important technologies.

04:15:25.000 --> 04:15:39.000
Moreover, the main orientation of such control is switched to competitive and preventive measures within the framework of international negotiations and international agreements.

04:15:39.000 --> 04:16:07.000
The struggle against industrial espionage is intensified. Moreover, there is a differentiation of countries in terms of access to high-tech. And, of course, getting into such a blacklist is not a good option for those countries of the transition economy that are developing their exports and imports.

04:16:07.000 --> 04:16:28.000
First of all, export control is taking place in relation to new goods and high-tech. As soon as these technologies and goods become more widespread in international trade, control is lifted.

04:16:29.000 --> 04:16:47.000
Now, the question of economic sanctions. I have already said that economic sanctions are a form of continuing political relations. The extreme case of modern political relations is military actions.

04:16:47.000 --> 04:17:08.000
Before military actions, under the framework of such an economic threat, some countries introduce economic sanctions. These sanctions have the greatest effect and effectiveness if they are introduced by the entire international community within the framework of the UN agreement, and not by individual countries.

04:17:08.000 --> 04:17:32.000
Nevertheless, many countries resort to economic sanctions as a preventive measure to solve political problems. In this case, the United States and the United States are the leaders in introducing sanctions. But Russia has also been often resorting to economic sanctions in recent years.

04:17:32.000 --> 04:17:58.000
If we classify economic sanctions, they can be divided into trade embargoes, point sanctions, and financial sanctions. In principle, the introduction of a trade embargo implies that export and import flows to this country are blocked, except for humanitarian flows in the framework of humanitarian aid, medicines, food products.

04:17:58.000 --> 04:18:25.000
Such a trade embargo has negative social and economic consequences, because the class or political leaders who were directed to implement these sanctions are not suffering. The third party suffering from the introduction of a trade embargo is the ordinary population of the country.

04:18:25.000 --> 04:18:54.000
Often, the introduction of a trade embargo has a negative effect. For example, the ban on the export and import of diamonds from the regions of South Africa, which were organized and directed against those militant groups that were developing military relations there at that time.

04:18:54.000 --> 04:19:12.000
The consequences of these sanctions had a negative effect in that as soon as the legal flows of export and import of diamonds were blocked, illegal trade developed, and prices for these diamonds increased.

04:19:12.000 --> 04:19:29.000
Thus, the profits from the global price growth were received by those groups against whom economic sanctions were directed in the form of a trade embargo. In modern conditions, point sanctions are preferred. Why?

04:19:29.000 --> 04:19:45.000
First, they are aimed at a separate group of goods. A more developed form of point sanctions is the direction of these restrictions on the activities of individual lists, on their movement between countries, entry and exit.

04:19:59.000 --> 04:20:22.000
Now a few words about the tariff policy of Russia. In principle, the processes of liberalization and protectionism are characteristic of the tariff policy of Russia over the past 15-17 years.

04:20:22.000 --> 04:20:37.000
It depends on the economic state of Russia, and on this, the policy of Russia changes either in favor of more liberalization or in favor of more rigid protectionism.

04:20:37.000 --> 04:21:02.000
In 1993, the first wave of the tariff policy of the Russian Federation was the introduction of the Customs Code, which was corrected in 2002. This correction was related to the liberalization of relations and various types of restrictions.

04:21:02.000 --> 04:21:22.000
This is because Russia, since 1995, has been actively preparing for the entry into the Customs Union. Multilateral, bilateral negotiations were held with virtually all member states of the Customs Union, and bilateral agreements were signed.

04:21:22.000 --> 04:21:48.000
In general, according to the system of protectionist measures, the advalorous rates of tariffs at the level of 5% or less cover about 40% of the entire nomenclature of the goods of Russian imports, and more than 44% of the volume of imports from far-away countries.

04:21:48.000 --> 04:22:08.000
In general, when one or another country finally enters the system of the World Trade Organization, the average tariff is calculated. Therefore, the tariff for some goods groups can be 0% on imports, and this is usually the raw materials groups, and for some, a fairly high tariff, for example, 15%.

04:22:08.000 --> 04:22:35.000
On average, this means that the average level of protectionist protection will be 7%. Accordingly, countries take into account the entire package of agreements and all types of goods and the entire tariff grid, and such an averaged level of protectionist protection is calculated.

04:22:35.000 --> 04:22:53.000
The trend of modern tariff policy in Russia is due to the fact that documents and legislative acts have been developed for a long time, which would not contradict the norms of the World Trade Organization.

04:22:53.000 --> 04:23:15.000
In particular, the principle of the WTO as the most favorable regime, which means that the tariff and other restrictions between the two countries that signed such a regime of the most favorable regime, these tariff restrictions are no worse than in relation to third countries.

04:23:15.000 --> 04:23:30.000
Thus, within the framework of these agreements, Russia signs agreements with 150 WTO member countries, which reduces the level of protectionist protection.

04:23:30.000 --> 04:23:50.000
What are the factors of weakening of the functions of Russian tariffs? In this case, this is due to the fact that the Russian market economy is still quite young. In fact, gray schemes of importing foreign goods are still spreading.

04:23:50.000 --> 04:24:12.000
As for industrial goods, long-term use goods, mainly technological goods that are imported from the Asian region. The next factor is the resorting.

04:24:12.000 --> 04:24:27.000
In this case, when determining the cost of the imported goods, it is possible to manipulate this cost and, accordingly, the goal of many companies is to reduce the import cost of the goods.

04:24:27.000 --> 04:24:45.000
The main problems here are related to the development of a system of measures that would allow to neutralize some subjective points, that is, when the personal interests of the customs officers will exceed the interests of the state.

04:24:45.000 --> 04:25:01.000
On the other hand, in Russia, as in the rest of the world, there are schemes for optimizing tax and customs payments, which again reduces the real level of tariff protection.

04:25:01.000 --> 04:25:27.000
The last component is the stock market import. The trend of stock market import is declining. Although, if we take the Russian economy of the early 90s, then most of the supply of long-term use goods, clothes from the near and far abroad was done by the stock market method on the Russian small-cap market.

04:25:28.000 --> 04:25:43.000
In modern conditions, stock market import is slowly transforming into a more established type of activity, into the activity of small and medium-sized companies, which are largely subject to state regulation.

04:25:43.000 --> 04:25:58.000
In this regard, it can be considered that the stock market import, as a factor that weakens the functions of the Russian tariff system, will slowly decline as the market relations in Russia develop.

04:25:58.000 --> 04:26:12.000
The next topic that we will discuss in our course is the international currency-financial system and currency regulation.

04:26:12.000 --> 04:26:27.000
The international currency-financial system is a form of organization of currency-financial relations, functioning independently and serving the international movement of goods and production factors.

04:26:27.000 --> 04:26:37.000
The development of the country's currency-financial system is influenced by a number of factors. First of all, it is the development of the country's economy.

04:26:37.000 --> 04:27:01.000
If the country has stable economic growth, if there is low inflation, low unemployment, then the attitude to the currency of the country is positive, and usually it is strong, stable and preferred by all economic agents.

04:27:02.000 --> 04:27:29.000
On the other hand, if we export goods and are the leaders in the export of goods to various industries, then the international demand for our currency for payment of export operations will be present in the world community.

04:27:29.000 --> 04:27:39.000
This is supported by our currency. The national and global political situation is also a factor in the influence of the country's currency-financial relations.

04:27:39.000 --> 04:28:01.000
The extreme variant of unstable political situation is wars. During the war, the currencies of the warring countries and parties usually weaken, there is a high level of inflation, and the currency is devalued.

04:28:01.000 --> 04:28:16.000
Economic sanctions and embargoes, which we talked about in the topic of state regulation of foreign trade relations, will certainly have a negative effect on the state of our currency.

04:28:16.000 --> 04:28:45.000
If some countries have introduced economic restrictions against our country in the form of sanctions and embargoes, it means that trade is beginning to be restrained, the supply of foreign currency to our country is reduced, export and import are reduced, and the situation is developing in the country when the trade deficit and payment balance are possible, which will certainly affect the level of our currency exchange rate.

04:28:46.000 --> 04:28:52.000
The power ratio between countries is another factor affecting the country's currency relations.

