05:40:06.000 --> 05:40:26.000
When a fixed currency rate is announced, a fairly rigid program for calculating and stabilizing the currency is carried out. They are practically trying not to include a money machine in order to solve the problem of budget deficit.

05:40:26.000 --> 05:40:54.000
The second benefit is stability and independence from currency speculations. But until this speculative attack is not carried out by some transnational banks, which often have more reserves than the national economy.

05:40:54.000 --> 05:41:01.000
I will repeat, this is the same example that happened with Japan in the second half of the 20th century.

05:41:01.000 --> 05:41:13.000
What are the negative aspects of the foreign currency rate? First, the loss of the ability to carry out independent monetary policy.

05:41:13.000 --> 05:41:31.000
Because you always have to adjust your currency rate to the monetary policy of the country to which you fix your currency rate.

05:41:31.000 --> 05:41:51.000
The second drawback is the import of foreign problems. If the currency rate of the country we are trying to rely on starts to fall, then there are problems for the domestic currency. It starts to get more expensive.

05:41:51.000 --> 05:42:19.000
For some countries, this is good, but for others it is a negative factor of export. On the other hand, if foreign currency starts to get more expensive, and our currency starts to get cheaper, then the joy of exporters does not always turn into the joy of the entire country's economy.

05:42:19.000 --> 05:42:36.000
The last drawback is the possibility of a collective attack on the fixed currency rate as a significant and terrible danger posed by the fixed currency rate.

